<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Serbs Urged To Stay in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- As the last of the Serbian troops  
pulled out of Kosovo today, the Yugoslav government tried to 
persuade thousands of fleeing Serb civilians to stay in the land 
considered the cradle of their culture. Serb civilians, fearful of 
a newly resurgent Kosovo Liberation Army, have fled the province 
only to find themselves unwelcome in the nation's capital, 
Belgrade. President Slobodan Milosevic, believed to see the Serb 
exodus as a possible pretext for an attempt to unseat him, has 
tried to conceal the problem. His government blocked attempts to 
set up tent cities and has urged the Serbs to return to Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Strong Action Pledged for Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	COLOGNE, Germany (AP) -- Leaders of the world's wealthiest  
countries concluded their annual summit today with a pledge to take 
``strong action'' to stabilize war-torn Kosovo. Russian Boris 
Yeltsin, joining the summit on its final day, declared that he was 
among friends despite being at odds over how to deal with Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic. In a concession to Yeltsin, the final 
communique did not include any language specifically prohibiting 
the delivery of reconstruction aid to Yugoslavia as long as 
Milosevic remains in power. 

</P>
<P>
	Pope Prays for Kosovo Peace  
</P>
<P>
	VATICAN CITY (AP) -- After his bout with the flu, Pope John Paul  
II today turned his attention to some of the world's trouble spots, 
praying that peace holds in Kosovo and that India and Pakistan work 
to end deadly fighting there. John Paul made numerous appeals to 
both Belgrade and NATO during the war to find a peaceful solution 
to the conflict in Yugoslavia. The pope returned to the Vatican on 
Thursday night from a 13-day trip to Poland. 

</P>
<P>
	Stephen King Alert After Surgery  
</P>
<P>
	LEWISTON, Maine (AP) -- Stephen King is alert and cracking jokes  
this morning after undergoing surgery for injuries sustained when 
he was hit by a car while walking near his home. The horror 
novelist underwent several hours of surgery at Central Maine 
Medical Center in Lewiston to ``deal with orthopedic kinds of 
injuries'' after he was struck by a Dodge Caravan yesterday 
afternoon, according to a hospital spokesman. King was conscious 
and alert after he emerged from the operation around 3:30 a.m. 

</P>
<P>
	Timor Group Won't Give Up Weapons  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- A pro-independence leader in East Timor  
said today his followers will not surrender their weapons as long 
as Indonesian troops remain in the troubled territory. Today is 
scheduled to be the first day of a disarmament period in advance of 
an Aug. 8 referendum that will let East Timorese choose between 
independence and autonomy within Indonesia. Violence between 
pro-independence and pro-Indonesian militias has increased as the 
U.N.-sponsored vote nears. 

</P>
<P>
	IOC Warns of Possible FBI Inquiry  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The International Olympic Committee  
warned its members today they could face questioning by the FBI -- 
and possible subpoenas -- in connection with the Salt Lake City 
bribery scandal. IOC director general Francois Carrard told the 
general assembly that the organization will offer legal assistance 
to members traveling to the United States. Carrard noted that 
several members have already been ``interviewed'' by the FBI as it 
investigates the vote-buying allegations surrounding Salt Lake's 
winning bid for the 2002 Winter Games. 

</P>
<P>
	Stars Win Stanley Cup in Triple OT  
</P>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- The Dallas Stars won the National Hockey  
League's Stanley Cup championship early today after ousting the 
Buffalo Sabres 2-1 in a grueling triple-overtime game to win the 
series 4-2. Brett Hull scored on a rebound at 14:51 of the third 
overtime, putting a rebound over weary goaltender Dominik Hasek as 
the Stars won hockey's biggest prize as much by exhaustion as 
execution. Hull ended the second-longest Stanley Cup finals game in 
history with his third goal of the series and third career overtime 
playoff goal. 

</P>
<P>
	Payne Stewart Leads U.S. Open  
</P>
<P>
	PINEHURST, N.C. (AP) -- Payne Stewart birdied the last hole after  
a long, punishing day on Pinehurst No. 2 yesterday to finish the 
third round as the only player under par at the U.S. Open. Stewart 
wound up with a 72 for 1-under 209, taking the lead into the final 
round for the second straight year. Phil Mickelson's 5-foot birdie 
putt on the 18th gave him a 73 and put him one stroke back at 
even-par 210. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief By DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
