<DOCNO> APW19990620.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 16:10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Gov. Mulls L.A. NFL Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Gov. Gray Davis reportedly is taking a strong  
role in negotiations to bring an NFL team to Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent weeks, Davis has spoken with prospective owners and  
NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue, and appointed a personal 
representative, Bill Chadwick, to represent the state in 
negotiations, the Los Angeles Times reported Sunday. The newspaper 
cited negotiation insiders it did not identify. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has become abundantly clear to the governor that there is  
promise for this deal,'' said one person who has spoken with Davis. 
``He wants to make this happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The role that the governor's office is playing is that of  
trying to make sure the state's interests are represented and 
protected,'' city councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas said. ``And of 
making sure that the deal goes down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, that doesn't mean Davis wants California taxpayers to  
foot any of the bill, an aide indicated. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the NFL wants to come to Los Angeles, that would be  
great,'' said Michael Bustamante, the governor's chief spokesman. 
``But the governor is not interested in spending any state money on 
this deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two development groups, one led by billionaire Eli Broad and the  
other by Hollywood dealmaker Michael Ovitz, are vying to bring an 
NFL team to the Los Angeles Coliseum. They have separate proposals 
to modernize the stadium, but the Ovitz plan could require more 
than $200 million in public financing. 
</P>
<P>
	The state has a say in the issue because it owns Exposition  
Park, which surrounds the Coliseum. Some of that land could be used 
for stadium parking. 
</P>
<P>
	Tagliabue was expected to come to Los Angeles this week as the  
NFL continues to look into the competing Coliseum plans. The league 
has set a Sept. 15 deadline for a workable plan in Los Angeles, and 
intends to bring all 31 owners together in Chicago on July 28 for a 
Los Angeles status report. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
