<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Approves New Rule on Gifts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- International Olympic Committee  
members may accept gifts only of ``nominal value'' under new rules 
adopted Sunday because of the Salt Lake City scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	On the final day of its four-day session in Seoul, the general  
assembly approved a code of ethics drawn up by the new IOC ethics 
commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel, consisting of three IOC members and five outside  
members, formulated rules of conduct for IOC delegates and other 
Olympic officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission was formed in May as a result of the Salt Lake  
scandal, in which 10 IOC members were removed for accepting more 
than $1 million in improper inducements during Salt Lake's winning 
bid for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The new code does away with the previous $200 gift limit, a rule  
that has been widely ignored. 
</P>
<P>
	``Only gifts of nominal value, in accordance with prevailing  
local custom, may be given or accepted by the Olympic parties, as a 
mark of respect or friendship,'' the new rule says. ``Any other 
gift must be passed on to the organization of which the beneficiary 
is a member.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other provisions of the ethics code:  
</P>
<P>
	--Olympic delegates can not ``solicit, accept or offer any  
concealed remuneration, commission, benefit or service of any 
nature connected with the organization of the Olympic Games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Hospitality offered to members and companions ``shall not  
exceed the standards prevailing in the host country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Olympic officials must avoid any conflict of interest and  
``must not act in a manner likely to bring the reputation of the 
Olympic movement into disrepute.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Bid cities ``shall refrain from approaching another party, or a  
third authority, with a view to obtaining any financial or 
political support'' inconsistent with the IOC manual. 
</P>
<P>
	The assembly also heard a preliminary report from the new IOC  
2000 reform commission, also created as a result of the Salt Lake 
scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	The 80-member panel, which met for the first time two weeks ago,  
is studying structural changes in the IOC and reforms in the 
bidding and selection process. 
</P>
<P>
	No concrete proposals were put forward Sunday.  
</P>
<P>
	The commission's three working groups will meet throughout the  
summer and submit final recommendations at the end of October. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC plans to hold a special session in December to ratify  
the reforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
