<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Trade Surplus Falls in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's trade surplus with the world dropped in May  
for the second month in a row, but its surplus with the United 
States remained on the rise, the government reported Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's merchandise trade surplus, the measure of all goods  
exported by a nation minus those imported, plunged 31.5 percent 
compared to the same month a year ago, the Finance Ministry said. 
</P>
<P>
	The May surplus -- $6.95 billion -- was lower than the average  
forecast of $7.90 billion by Tokyo-based economists surveyed by Dow 
Jones. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, the surplus decreased 14.6 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	Japan's politically sensitive trade surplus with the United  
States, however, rose in May, increasing 14.9 percent to $4.35 
billion, the ministry said. The surplus rose 2.1 percent in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan, fighting its worst recession in 50 years, has been under  
heavy pressure from the United States and other trading partners to 
rein in the surplus by bolstering its weak economy to spark demand 
for imports. 
</P>
<P>
	The ministry said the recent falls in the overall surplus  
indicate that the trade surplus is on a gradual declining track. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first five months of this year, the surplus averaged a  
fall of 8.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The decline was mainly because exports fell at a faster pace  
than imports. Overall, exports were weighed down by falls in steel, 
computer parts, cars, and ships, a ministry official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's politically sensitive exports of steel to the United  
States continued falling since last December, down 56.9 percent at 
$125.7 million in May. Imports from the United States fell largely 
because of declining aircraft imports, the official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall imports slipped only 3.3 percent because of a 6.5  
percent increase in crude oil prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The ministry said May was the first time that Japan's trade  
surplus had fallen two months in a row since January 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's trade surplus had consistently grown more than 20  
percent for a string of months until last October. After that trend 
was broken by a 16.2 percent drop in November, the surplus 
alternated back and forth between falls and rises until the last 
two months. 
</P>
<P>
	In fiscal 1998, Japan's overall trade surplus rose 23 percent  
from the previous year to reach the second highest total ever 
recorded. 
</P>
<P>
	The 31.5 percent decline in the surplus in May was the largest  
since August 1996, when it plummeted 35.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar averaged 120.15 yen in May, down from 132.29 yen a  
year earlier. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 09:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
