<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Leads N.Y. Senate Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Most New York voters don't care that Hillary  
Clinton has never lived here and don't believe her role as first 
lady would create a conflict with her potential Senate campaign, 
according to a Daily News poll released Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll gave Mrs. Clinton a slight lead in a hypothetical  
Senate race with New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. The first 
lady led the mayor 47 to 39 percent, but the poll had a margin of 
error of plus or minus 4 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	Both the mayor and Mrs. Clinton are likely candidates for the  
seat being vacated by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y. The 
election is 16 months away. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll, conducted by Blum &AMP; Weprin Associates, also found that  
nearly three-fourths of voters do not feel it is a conflict for 
Mrs. Clinton to run for Senate while still serving as first lady. 
</P>
<P>
	More than two-thirds said Mrs. Clinton's lack of state residency  
would not keep them from voting for her. 
</P>
<P>
	The random survey of 805 registered voters around the state was  
conducted last week. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
