<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Ships went on alert Sunday as the first  
hurricane of the eastern north Pacific this season generated high 
waves and heavy rainfall along Mexico's central coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Hurricane Adrian was centered about 345 miles south of the tip  
of the Baja California Peninsula and moving to the west-northwest 
at 14 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Hurricane Center in Miami reported maximum  
sustained winds of 85 mph. Late Saturday, the storm had reached 
hurricane status when its wind speed surpassed 74 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities on the Baja California Peninsula were preparing to  
order residents to leave hillsides and river banks if necessary, 
the government news agency Notimex said. 
</P>
<P>
	The area includes the resorts of San Blas, Puerto Vallarta,  
Manzanillo, Ixtapa-Zihuatanejo, Acapulco, and Puerto Escondido. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuela's president said Sunday that  
he will ignore a ruling banning him from campaigning for candidates 
for a new assembly that will rewrite the country's constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	``I declare that I'm campaigning now more than ever,'' Hugo  
Chavez said during his weekly radio program. ``If they want to put 
me in jail, well, go ahead and do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Venezuelan law prohibits Chavez and other high-level public  
officials from taking part in the campaign, which officially starts 
next Thursday, the National Electoral Council says. The election is 
July 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez, who took office in February, has called the council's  
ruling ridiculous. He has already been promoting candidates backed 
by his leftist Patriotic Pole coalition, which is expected to 
dominate the race. 
</P>
<P>
	His critics say he wants to use the assembly to concentrate  
power in his hands. 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez, the leader of a failed 1992 coup attempt, says a new  
constitution is needed to clean up rampant corruption and ease 
widespread poverty. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) -- Nicaraguan bank regulators have  
ordered top officials of a Guatemalan-led bank detained for alleged 
fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicaragua's bank regulation agency said it has evidence that  
Banco del Sur made a series of fraudulent operations that were 
detected in the past few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Late Saturday it ordered the capture of bank president Mario  
Arnoldo Hernandez Colindres, the bank's manager and its auditor. It 
was unclear whether any of the men had been arrested Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez Colindres is a partner in a Guatemalan financial  
group, Financiera del Sur, which allegedly issued false investment 
certificates for the equivalent of $1 million to a Guatemalan woman 
earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicaraguan Superintendent of Banks Angel Navarro said  
investigators also found that Banco del Sur had no backing for 
between $10 million and $15 million registered in its holdings. 
</P>
<P>
	Regulators named a provisional administrator Saturday to ensure  
that Banco del Sur opens its doors for business Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- President Fernando Henrique  
Cardoso's popularity has plunged to its lowest level, according to 
a poll released Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll found 44 percent of Brazilians thought his government  
was ``bad'' or ``very bad,'' while only 16 percent described it as 
``good'' or ``very good,'' according to the polling group 
Datafolha. 
</P>
<P>
	The results put Cardoso's popularity at its lowest since he took  
office in 1995 and for the first time show that a majority believe 
he is doing a poor job, said the newspaper Folha de Sao Paulo, 
which also published the poll. 
</P>
<P>
	In past months, Cardoso's popularity has been hurt by economic  
austerity measures, record unemployment, and a scandal involving 
government favoritism over privatization of the state telephone 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll was based on interviews with 12,023 Brazilians between  
June 9 and 11. The margin of error is two percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- A weekend camping trip turned into  
a tragedy after nine children drowned in a river in northeast 
Brazil, a news agency reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The children, between the ages of 8-14, died Saturday after  
entering the Poti River to recover a soccer ball, according to the 
Agencia Estado. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident occurred near the city of Teresina, about 1500  
miles north of Rio de Janeiro. 
</P>
<P>
	Local police said they are looking for a man who had accompanied  
the children on the outing. Authorities say they believe there may 
be several other victims. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- More than 40 percent of babies in  
Puerto Rico are born to unwed parents, a study by the University of 
Puerto Rico shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Results of the study, published Saturday in El Nuevo Dia  
newspaper, show 46 percent of the 64,214 births on the island in 
1997 were to unmarried parents, up from 43 percent in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	In 31 percent of the cases in 1995, the parents lived together.  
In the other 12 percent, the mother was the sole head of the 
household, researchers at the university's Medical Sciences Campus 
found. 
</P>
<P>
	The rate of births out of wedlock has risen steadily since 1975,  
when it stood at 18 percent. In 1980, the rate was 21 percent; in 
1985, 28 percent; and in 1990, 37 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers said of Puerto Rico's 78 municipalities,  
northeastern Moca had the lowest rate of unwed parents in 1995, 21 
percent. The highest, 62 percent, was in southern Santa Isabel. 
</P>
<P>
	They also noted that 69 percent of married couples had their  
babies in private hospitals, while most unwed mothers gave birth in 
public hospitals. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
