<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Son Makes Ode to Father's Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- As a young man, Hy Meyerowitz was a vaudevillian,  
a sharp Catskills comedian who was the consummate toastmaster. 
</P>
<P>
	As an old man, his mind dulled by Alzheimer's disease,  
Meyerowitz still cracked one-liners, but they had lost their edge. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, three years before he died, his son Meyerowitz's son,  
photographer and filmmaker Joel Meyerowitz, decided to spring his 
father from an assisted-living facility in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., 
and take him and his own son on a road trip. 
</P>
<P>
	Prodding and probing the elderly man's imagination and memory,  
the three generations traveled back to New York City -- to Harlem, 
where the elder Meyerowitz spent his childhood, and to the Bronx, 
where he raised his family. 
</P>
<P>
	Casually sprawled in the back seat, drifting in and out of  
lucidity, Meyerowitz recalled snippets of the past. Like the time 
the family parakeet, Melvin Meyerowitz, flew away and was returned 
by a neighbor after he spoke the family's name. 
</P>
<P>
	Joel Meyerowitz and his son Sasha, 30, a cinematographer living  
in Boulder, Colo., filmed the trip with a camcorder. The result is 
``Pop,'' an hour-long ``Frontline'' documentary airing Tuesday at 9 
p.m. EDT on PBS. 
</P>
<P>
	The film is a montage of footage from the trip, and videos of  
Meyerowitz and his wife as young parents with three young sons. 
</P>
<P>
	Meyerowitz grew up during the vaudeville era. Quick-witted and  
spunky, his powers of observation made him the neighborhood sage. 
After marrying, he sold dry-cleaning supplies for a chemical 
company, but the entertainer in him never faded. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was a dancer, he was a Chaplin mimic,'' Joel Meyerowitz  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	He was also the neighborhood Solomon. ``I remember that people  
would gather in front of our window and they would yell ... And 
he'd come to the window and he'd adjudicate from the window.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His wit and sharp mind helped to mask his Alzheimer's symptoms  
for many years. 
</P>
<P>
	``When he started nailing $100 bills to the wall and hanging  
pictures on them and driving my mother to the supermarket and 
driving away, we started to realize, `Uh, oh, trouble,''' Joel 
Meyerowitz said. 
</P>
<P>
	While driving from Florida to New York, Joel tries to get his  
father to think rationally and to block out the obsessions forming 
in his mind: imagining his wife is cheating on him, or looking for 
coins on the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout the three-week trip, Joel tries to stimulate his  
father's mind with questions about his other sons and what they do 
for a living. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, Joel tries to get Hy to notice an absurd roadside  
sign, telling him he always enjoyed having his father point out 
unusual objects or situations to him. 
</P>
<P>
	``The things that were new to you were such funny things and  
such odd things. You always were showing (them) to me. And I know 
that's why I take pictures now -- because you pointed out all these 
things to me as a kid,'' Joel Meyerowitz said. 
</P>
<P>
	The film's producer and director, he is an acclaimed  
photographer who has authored 12 books, including ``Cape Light,'' 
scenic photos of Cape Cod and the Islands. 
</P>
<P>
	Having completed ``Pop,'' his first film, Joel Meyerowitz said  
his experiences may persuade him to explore care of the elderly in 
another film. 
</P>
<P>
	Hy Meyerowitz's wife of 65 years died at 86, several weeks after  
he returned to Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Joel Meyerowitz then moved his father to a nursing home in New  
York's East Village, just blocks from his own home. Hy died there 
in November at the age of 90. The day he died, ``Pop'' was being 
shown at the Museum of Modern Art in New York and at the Hampton 
Film Festival on Long Island. 
</P>
<P>
	Sasha Meyerowitz said the trip allowed him to discover new sides  
of his grandfather's personality. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really kind of fell in love with him on that trip. I think I  
was beginning to see his personality and his passion for life, his 
basic being,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``He read people beautifully,'' Joel Meyerowitz said. ``He used  
humor as a lever. I guess that was the thrilling part for both my 
son and myself: to see someone with a disability and not yield to 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	`20/20': New research suggests that workaholics may be hurting  
not only themselves but their children. Correspondent Cynthia 
McFadden reports the startling results of a study pointing to the 
serious effects a parent's workaholism may have on children's 
emotional stability. It airs tonight on ``20/20,'' at 8 p.m. EDT on 
ABC. Connie Chung and Charles Gibson anchor. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
