<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise in Midday Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The U.S. dollar surged against the yen in morning  
trading Monday, boosted by talk that the Bank of Japan bought 
dollars to stem the Japanese currency's rise. Tokyo stocks 
advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.94 yen in early trading, up 2.62 yen from  
late Friday in Tokyo and also above its late Friday New York level 
of 120.44 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 281.95 points,  
or 1.62 percent, ending the morning session at 17,713.21. On 
Friday, the average fell 39.19 points, or 0.22 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, traders believed the Bank of Japan bought  
dollars and sold yen Monday morning, although it was not 
immediately known at which level the bank stepped in. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders believe the apparent intervention came shortly after the  
Finance Ministry announced that Japan's trade surplus shrank by a 
greater-then-expected 31.5 percent in May. 
</P>
<P>
	``If in fact the BOJ did intervene above the 120.00 yen level,  
it shows their resolve to push the dollar up even further,'' said 
Shuji Takano, assistant manager of foreign exchange at ABN AMRO 
Bank in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	If the intervention did occur, it would mark the fourth time in  
less than two weeks that Japan's central bank has done so. On 
Friday, at the BOJ's bequest, the European Central Bank bought 
euros for yen. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 126.80 yen, up from  
122.73 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices started higher as foreign investors  
continued to buy stocks on hopes that Japan's tenuous economic 
recovery may finally be picking up steam. 
</P>
<P>
	During a three-day meeting of the Group of Seven major nations,  
ended Sunday in Cologne, Germany, other participating leaders 
maintained pressure on Japan to do more to ensure it is on a 
domestic-led growth path. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said that the Japanese government  
will take every measure available to ensure stable growth. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 213 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.7400 percent from Friday's finish of 1.7300 percent, 
driving its price down to 97.10 yen from 97.18 yen. 
</P>
<P>
 *(km-may-dj) 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
