<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stewart Moves Toward U.S. Open Title  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PINEHURST, N.C. (AP) -- Instead of backing up to the field, Payne  
Stewart came out charging Sunday in the final round of the U.S. 
Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, who won the Open in 1991 and was a runner-up in '93 and  
'98, started the day with a one-shot lead in the light mist at 
Pinehurst No. 2. He quickly grabbed a two-shot margin over top 
contenders Phil Mickelson, Tiger Woods and David Duval with a 
15-foot birdie putt on the first hole. 
</P>
<P>
	After giving a shot back on the second hole when he missed the  
green right and his first pitch shot rolled back to his feet, 
Stewart stuck his approach shot on No. 3 within three feet for 
another birdie. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart, 42, lost a four-stroke lead to champion Lee Janzen in  
the final round of the Open last year at The Olympic Club. But he 
looked solid this time around as he made the turn at 2 under for 
the tourney. 
</P>
<P>
	The man known for his knickers found himself with at least a  
two-shot margin over everyone but Mickelson, his playing partner, 
who was within one shot after the soggy front nine. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods, looking for his first victory in a major since the '97  
Masters, got to even par for the tournament after making a 4-foot 
birdie on his first hole, but he flew his approach shot over the 
green at Nos. 3 and 5 and made bogeys. 
</P>
<P>
	Duval, the No. 1 player in the world, began with a par save from  
the woods on No. 1 and two birdies on his first three holes, but 
once again found trouble at his nemesis hole all week -- the par-3 
No. 6. He missed a 5-footer there for par that dropped him three 
shots behind Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	Duval missed another 5-footer for par two holes later and his  
double-bogey on the par-3 ninth hole dropped one of this week's 
favorites from contention after a front-nine 2-over-par 37. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Mickelson couldn't put together anything early in his  
round, stringing together six straight pars, including a pair of 
par-saving 8-footers on the first two holes. He then sank a 25-foot 
birdie putt on No. 7 to pull closer to Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Herron, the lesser known of the leaders, lost his chance for  
a major title with a double-bogey on No. 6 and bogeys on the next 
two holes. He started the day two shots behind Stewart, who made a 
fabulous sand save for par on the ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	Stewart's 1-under 34 on the front tied Mickelson and Vijay Singh  
for the best opening nine holes among Sunday's final three groups. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 09:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cormorants Overrunning Great Lakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BASS ISLAND, N.Y. (AP) -- The battle is joined.  
</P>
<P>
	With the sun glaring hot overhead, the small skiff slides into  
shore. The island is already occupied. The attackers step out, 
quickly gathering their wits and weapons as they seek their 
targets. 
</P>
<P>
	The enemy puts up no resistance. They flee to a safe distance  
offshore to watch the destruction of their homes and the death of 
their young. 
</P>
<P>
	New York state wildlife biologist Jim Farquhar repeatedly stabs  
a 30-foot-long metal pole into peeling and waste-washed trees to 
dislodge 2- and 3-foot wide nests from the branches. The 3-inch 
blue-green eggs fall to the ground; those not broken also will die, 
abandoned. 
</P>
<P>
	The effort to control the exploding population of cormorants on  
eastern Lake Ontario has become a war -- not to Farquhar and his 
assistant, but to the anglers, fishing guides and businesses whose 
leisure and livelihoods are linked to the fish in the lake. 
</P>
<P>
	It is a conflict that is under way in other Great Lakes states,  
as well as on fish farms in the South, as the voracious diving bird 
has become a destructive invasion force under federal government 
protection. 
</P>
<P>
	``Personally, I like cormorants. I think they're a pretty neat  
bird. They are adaptable. They have done well despite humans. I 
admire that,'' Farquhar said, setting sight on another nest high 
above the ground. It is one of 50 he will destroy this day to keep 
the birds from colonizing this 5-acre island. 
</P>
<P>
	In eastern Lake Ontario alone, cormorants consumed 87.5 million  
fish in 1998, including 1.3 million smallmouth bass, the lake's 
most popular sport fish, according to a New York state report. 
</P>
<P>
	Fishermen caught about 36,000 bass.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was either us or the birds,'' said Ron Ditch, who faces  
fines and six months home confinement for admitting in federal 
court that he helped eight other men, including his three sons, 
kill up to 2,000 cormorants last summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody was going to do anything about it. We had to save  
ourselves,'' said Ditch, a longtime fishing guide. 
</P>
<P>
	Ditch blames the cormorants for devastating his 49-year-old  
charter business and forcing one of his sons to move to Florida to 
find work. Up and down the lake's eastern shoreline, the complaint 
is the same from tackle shops, restaurants, hotels and other 
businesses whose prosperity depends on how well the fish are 
biting. 
</P>
<P>
	Cormorants have been a federally protected species since 1918  
when they were included in the original Migratory Bird Treaty 
between the United States and Canada. Since then, Mexico, Japan and 
Russia have become parties to the treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	While the birds' foes say the cormorants have outgrown their  
protected status, changing it would be an international issue, said 
Diane Pence, a U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service spokeswwoman in 
Hadley, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	``Besides, if we took away their protected status, they would be  
severely persecuted again. We would never completely take away 
their protection,'' Pence said. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the federal agency is in the early stages of piecing  
together a regional control plan, while allowing states some 
interim steps. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, Farquhar and his colleagues are destroying nests on  
selected islands to keep the birds from establishing new colonies, 
and they are spraying eggs with oil to suffocate the embryos inside 
to cancel out this year's hatching season. 
</P>
<P>
	One of six species of cormorants, the black, double-crested  
cormorant is native to the Canadian Plains but has moved eastward 
and southward looking for new breeding areas. It prefers remote 
islands, away from humans and predators. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists counted 15,800 breeding pairs in 48 colonies in the  
U.S.-Canadian Great Lakes during a 1990 census. In 1997, there were 
more than 85,300 breeding pairs in 159 colonies. Scientists 
estimate there are three to four single birds for every pair. 
Unchecked, the cormorant population is increasing by about 7 
percent a year, said John Trapp, a U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service 
biologist. 
</P>
<P>
	Distantly related to pelicans, cormorants first appeared on Lake  
Ontario in the late 1930s. Today, the Little Galloo Colony in 
eastern Lake Ontario is the largest cormorant nesting area in the 
Great Lakes with more than 7,000 pairs. It is there that the 
cormorant problem is at its worst. How much longer that will be 
true is uncertain. 
</P>
<P>
	``We see them everywhere,'' said Malcolm Both, secretary for the  
Great Lakes Sport Fishing Council, an umbrella organization for 90 
local and regional associations. 
</P>
<P>
	``So far, the impact has been on small areas. But there's a  
significant concern that soon others will be experiencing problems 
like New York,'' said Both, of Racine, Wis. 
</P>
<P>
	Already, on northern Lake Michigan, commercial fishermen  
complain of finding cormorants entangled in their underwater nets. 
On Lake Erie, the birds are blamed for a decline in the perch and 
walleye fisheries. 
</P>
<P>
	The once-verdant Little Galloo, a 55-acre island located five  
miles offshore in Lake Ontario, looks like a lunar landscape. The 
cormorants have stripped it of its flora for their nests. A blanket 
of guana coats the ground and has poisoned the trees. The other 
birds that once roosted here -- including rare black-crowned night 
herons -- have left. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, animal-rights groups, whose attention was galvanized  
by last summer's slaughter, monitor the predicament, ready to 
intervene on behalf of the birds. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not convinced the population of cormorants needs to be  
reduced just because they are competing with some sports anglers 
who want trophy smallmouth bass,'' said Michael Markarian, 
executive director of Fund for Animals, a New York City-based 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	``The cormorants are doing what they need to do to survive, and  
that's eat fish,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Some interim steps allowed by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service  
to control cormorants: 
</P>
<P>
	-- In Vermont, state officials are using small-scale fireworks to  
harass cormorants into abandoning their nests on Bixby Island in 
Lake Champlain. The cormorants are blamed for defoliating the 
island and driving off other birds. Cormorants first came to Lake 
Champlain in 1972; today, there are 3,000 nesting pairs on a 
handful of islands in the lake. 
</P>
<P>
	-- In Arkansas and 12 other states, fish farmers can obtain  
federal permits to shoot pilfering cormorants, which find easy 
pickings at the farm ponds. The federal government considers the 
farm fish personal property and allows the farmers to take steps to 
protect it. The other states are Alabama, Florida, Georgia, 
Kentucky, Louisiana, Minnesota, Mississippi, North Carolina, 
Oklahoma, South Carolina, Tennessee and Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	-- In Orleans, Mass., residents want permission to shoot  
migrating cormorants, which roost in their Cape Cod seaside village 
on the way to their winter home in the Louisiana wetlands. There 
are so many birds, residents complained, that they cannot hang out 
clothes to dry or sit outside to eat because of all the bird 
droppings. 
</P>
<P>
	The first cormorant control efforts date back to 1944-1952 when  
Maine was allowed to spray oil on more than 200,000 cormorant eggs 
to reduce its coastal colonies. The oil suffocates the eggs' 
embryos. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Some facts about cormorants:  
</P>
<P>
	-- The double-crested cormorant is a glossy black goose-sized  
bird with webbed feet. Its bill is hooked at the tip and it has an 
orange pouch underneath. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The cormorant's feathers lack oil for waterproofing, which  
enables it to swim underwater, propelled by its webbed feet. 
Because its feathers get wet, cormorants are frequently seen 
sunning on rocks with their wings outspread. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Cormorants can dive up to 40 feet underwater. Chinese  
fishermen use them as a tool to help catch fish. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Cormorants spend about 60 minutes a day fishing. An average  
cormorant will capture about five fish an hour. Their feeding range 
is about 25 miles. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Cormorants are opportunistic feeders; they eat the most  
readily available species. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Cormorants live an average of 15 years.  
</P>
<P>
	-- Female cormorants usually lay three to four eggs per clutch,  
but can lay as many as seven. They fledge two to three chicks per 
clutch. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Their nests are made of twigs and whatever flotsam or debris  
they can find. They are 2- to 3-feet wide. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The North America double-crested cormorant population is  
estimated at between 1 million and 2 million. About 70 percent are 
still located in their native territory, the prairie lakes of 
Alberta, Manitoba and Saskatchewan. About 12 percent are located in 
the Great Lakes. 
</P>
<P>
	-- The double-crested cormorant has been found breeding now in 40  
states, all 10 Canadian provinces, Mexico, Cuba and the Bahamas. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 15:26:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Avery Johnson Knows About Traveling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- As many places as he's been and as many times as  
he's had to move, Avery Johnson plays basketball with a basic sense 
of insecurity. 
</P>
<P>
	He's not a franchise player like Tim Duncan or David Robinson,  
each a 7-footer, each able to dominate games with brute strength. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, he's a journeyman point guard two wins from an NBA  
championship. Johnson is coach Gregg Popovich's on-court presence 
for the San Antonio Spurs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always feel I'm one step from being cut,'' Johnson said  
Sunday. ``Pop might wake up one day and say, `We don't want you 
anymore.' That keeps you humble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And that's a permanent state of mind for the guy with the  
high-pitched voice who's been playing the point in the NBA for 11 
years after not even being drafted out of college. 
</P>
<P>
	This is the third time Johnson's NBA odyssey has passed through  
San Antonio. The other stops were in Seattle, where he signed 
originally as an undrafted free agent in 1988, Denver, Houston and 
Golden State. He even spent time in the U.S. Basketball League with 
the long-forgotten Palm Beach Stingrays. 
</P>
<P>
	He once was traded by Seattle for a second-round draft pick in a  
league where only the first-round picks usually mean anything. And 
the SuperSonics had to wait seven years to collect the draft 
choice. 
</P>
<P>
	He's been waived twice and signed as a free agent seven times.  
He has, as they say, been around the block. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some guys get older and worse,'' he said. ``I got older and  
better. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a cerebral player in a lot of ways. The game is mental for  
me, not physical anymore. I'm not a 150-pound guy out of Southern 
University anymore. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only way to measure how good I am is by wins.''  
</P>
<P>
	And the Spurs won more games than anybody else in the league  
this season, with Johnson averaging 9.7 points and 7.4 assists and 
keeping the big guys underneath happy. 
</P>
<P>
	``With Tim and Dave, I'm always mindful of their shot  
attempts,'' he said. ``If I have to force the issue, I'll pass up 
the shot to get them the ball. You've got to keep Dave involved or 
he tends to float a little.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If that sounds a little critical, it's not unusual. Johnson  
speaks his mind and on his mind is how the Spurs, flirting with all 
kinds of playoff records for wins, are playing right now. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our offense has not been good,'' he said, shaking his head.  
``Our spacing, our passing. We're passing when we shouldn't be and 
not passing when we should. We're not close to being good 
offensively.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson has played well, with 14 points and 13 assists in the  
first two wins. He thinks he can turn his game up even further. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I don't have control and we make too many empty passes  
and shot clock violations, that's bad,'' he said. ``We've got to do 
a better job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And yet, they continue to win.  
</P>
<P>
	Johnson is 34 and brings maturity to a lineup where 23-year-old  
Tim Duncan has become the main man. AJ watches Duncan's approach to 
the postseason with some interest. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tim is excited,'' he said. ``But our appreciation level is  
different because our frame of reference is different.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duncan, remember, was a lottery player, the No. 1 pick in the  
draft. He didn't have to go shopping for a team. And he'll never be 
traded for a second-round pick. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Palm Beach Stingrays?  
</P>
<P>
	No chance.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 15:26:00 </DATE_TIME>
