<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 11:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Graf Finds Happiness in Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- Steffi Graf just turned 30, but she  
seems to be turning back time. 
</P>
<P>
	On the eve of Wimbledon a year ago, her WTA Tour ranking had  
plunged to 91, the result of an injury layoff and knee surgery that 
caused her to miss four Grand Slams. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Graf is fresh from winning the French Open -- her 22nd major  
singles title -- and there's again talk of her tying Margaret 
Court's record of 24. There's also talk this may be her last 
Wimbledon. 
</P>
<P>
	She's won here seven times, twice beating Martina Navratilova  
and Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario in the finals as well as Monica Seles, 
Gabriela Sabatini and Jana Novotna. This year she's seeded No. 2 
behind Martina Hingis, conjuring thoughts of a rematch of French 
Open finalists. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the beginning of the year,'' she said, ``things didn't go  
so well. But in the last two week I've rediscovered the pleasure of 
tennis. I feel more open now, more able to express my feeling 
without the fear of losing my concentration. I've got rid of the 
burden of records. ... Maybe that's why I've started winning 
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Graf said her announcement to never return to the French Open  
was spontaneous, knowing it would be impossible to top her dramatic 
win over Hingis. Would a Wimbledon victory bring a similar 
announcement? 
</P>
<P>
	``You never know, it could be my last one,'' said Graf, who is  
two short of Navratilova's record of nine Wimbledon singles titles. 
``But I'm not thinking about that right now. I don't want to talk 
about something that may never happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *UNEASY NOVOTNA:* This is a different Wimbledon for Jana Novotna  
-- and it won't be an easy one. 
</P>
<P>
	She's the defending champion with hardly anyone picking the  
widely experienced grass-court player to repeat, partially because 
of a severe ankle injury sustained playing doubles with Natasha 
Zvereva at the French Open. 
</P>
<P>
	``We crashed into one another and I stepped on Natasha's foot  
and turned my ankle,'' she said. ``This is the worst sprain I've 
had in years. I was carried off the court I was in a lot of pain 
for a few days. I'm extra pleased with the progress I've made. When 
this happened I thought Wimbledon was probably over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Novotna has had a difficult summer and a poor clay-court season.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a struggle and I have to be ready to fight,''  
she said. ``I don't want to look too far. My goal after my sprain 
was to play at Wimbledon. That was my biggest goal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Always a robust looking player, Novotna has been surpassed by a  
younger generation. ``Women's tennis is becoming just a power game 
-- very simple, strong and physical,'' she said, noting the lack of 
serve and volley players. ``It's not about variety or thinking 
game. It's just becoming pure power. Whoever hits harder is the 
winner.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BECKER'S BACK:@ Three-time champion Boris Becker is back after  
saying two years ago he'd played his last Wimbledon. Now the 
31-year-old German says this will be his last one. 
</P>
<P>
	He faces Scot Miles Maclagan in a winnable first-round match and  
then is likely to face fellow German Nicolas Kiefer. If he survives 
until the fourth round, look for him U.S. Open champion Pat Rafter 
to give him his final good-bye. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	DRUG TESTS:@ Widely criticized for being too lax on drug  
testing, the International Tennis Federation says it will carry out 
15-20 random test daily at Wimbledon -- and test every loser from 
the quarterfinal stage. 
</P>
<P>
	ITF spokesman Alun James said the number was slightly up from a  
year ago when former Australian Open champion Petr Korda became the 
first player to test positive at Wimbledon. Korda, who is in a 
legal battle with the ITF over the test, announced his retirement 
last week after failing to qualify for Wimbledon. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PICK ME:* Looking for a Wimbledon winner? Goran Ivanisevic,  
three times a Wimbledon runner-up and loser in a five-set final a 
year ago to Pete Sampras, is picking himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm feeling good and I'm not the favorite. I find I always  
play better without that added pressure. I will certainly bet on 
myself to win at Wimbledon, it's the one tournament that I would 
love to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Is a third rematch in the final with Sampras possible?  
</P>
<P>
	``Sampras loves Wimbledon and the whole place is like his  
home,'' Ivanisevic said. ``Grass suits his game, and to beat him in 
the final would be the ultimate achievement.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *THE ODDS:* Sampras is 11-8 to win his sixth Wimbledon,  
according to British bookmakers William Hill. He is followed by Tim 
Henman 7-1, Richard Krajicek 8-1, Pat Rafter 9-1, Greg Rusedski 
14-1, Andre Agassi and Ivanisevic 16-1, Mark Philippoussis 20-1 and 
Karol Kucera 25-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Hingis tops the women at 6-4 followed by Graf 3-1, Venus  
Williams 5-1, Lindsay Davenport and Monica Seles 12-1, Novotna 
16-1, Anna Kournikova 33-1, Nathalie Tauziat 40-1 and Arantxa 
Sanchez-Vicario 50-1. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *RAIN, OF COURSE:* The last three Wimbledons have been battered  
by record rain. This one should be better, but with a wet start. 
Monday should be nearly shower-free, with Tuesday bringing light 
showers and Wednesday calling for a chance of heavy rain. That 
should give way to clear skies though Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``And for the second week the outlook is reasonable, quite good  
with a light risk of showers,'' said forecaster Andrew Honeyman of 
the British Met Office. ``It has to be better than recent years.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
