<DOCNO> APW19990620.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 18:10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Radio Host Clifton Fadiman Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANIBEL ISLAND, Fla. (AP) -- Clifton Fadiman, a writer, book  
editor, radio and television entertainer who was host of the 
popular radio show ``Information Please'' in the 1930s, died 
Sunday. He was 95. 
</P>
<P>
	Fadiman, who died at his son's home, was diagnosed with terminal  
pancreatic cancer last October, said his wife, Annalee Whitmore 
Fadiman. The two lived on Captiva Island, Fla., off Florida's Gulf 
coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Fadiman most recently served as general editor on several  
publications, including ``World Poetry'' and the fourth edition of 
one of his own works, ``The Lifetime Reading Plan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He penned more than 65 introductions to a wide range of editions  
including ``War and Peace,'' ``The Martian Chronicles'' and ``Six 
by Seuss.'' He was awarded the National Book Award for 
Distinguished Contribution to American Letters in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had a quick, entertaining mind and was never boring for a  
second,'' Mrs. Fadiman said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1985, he was honored as an editor for ``A World Treasury of  
Children's Literature,'' Britannica Junior Encyclopedia, the Young 
Children's Encyclopedia and other works, winning the Dorothy C. 
McKenzie Award for contribution to children's literature. 
</P>
<P>
	But for many who knew him, Fadiman probably will be best  
remembered for his mostly anonymous role as senior judge for the 
Book-of-the-Month Club. It's a relationship he fostered for more 
than half a century, starting in the early '40s. Despite losing his 
sight, he continued to make selections, listening to audio versions 
well into his 90s. 
</P>
<P>
	Fadiman referred to a quotation he attributed to Aldous Huxley,  
who expressed concerns about science destroying human and political 
values in his 1932 satirical novel ``Brave New World,'' as a theme 
in his own life. ``Let's be a little kinder to each other,'' 
Fadiman said during an interview in March 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of New York, Fadiman began his career -- a term he  
reserved for sports figures -- in 1925 as a teacher at Ethical 
Culture High School, better known as Fieldston. 
</P>
<P>
	Four years later, he switched professions, first becoming  
associate editor and then editor-in-chief at Simon &AMP; Schuster. 
During that time, Fadiman wrote articles and became Book Editor for 
The New Yorker, a position he held from 1933 to 1943. 
</P>
<P>
	Fadiman also tried his hand at radio, serving as master of  
ceremonies for the top-10 hit ``Information Please,'' which ran for 
a decade starting in 1938. The show consisted of a panel of experts 
who were quizzed by the audience. That was followed by the 
television program ``This is Show Business,'' and another stint on 
radio as the host of ``Conversation'' from 1954-57. 
</P>
<P>
	He became a member of the selection committee for the  
Book-of-the-Month Club in 1944, eventually taking on the titles of 
senior judge, chief editorial adviser and finally chairman emeritus 
in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Fadiman, whose two hobbies consisted of wine and ``the avoidance  
of exercise,'' had a simple lifelong work ethic. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't retire,'' he said. ``I wouldn't know what to do.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 16:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Son of Sam' Killer Upset Over Film </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- David Berkowitz, the ``Son of Sam'' serial  
killer, says he is saddened by the upcoming release of Spike Lee's 
movie based on his 1977 murder spree. 
</P>
<P>
	``This madness, the ugliness of the past is resurfacing again --  
all because some people want to make some money,'' Berkowitz said 
in a prison interview with The New York Times published Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Following his arrest 22 years ago, the former postal clerk  
confessed to fatally shooting six people and wounding seven others. 
He later said he took orders from a black Labrador retriever named 
Sam that was owned by a neighbor. 
</P>
<P>
	Berkowitz, 46, said he is now a born-again Christian.  
</P>
<P>
	``I pray for Spike Lee and his family, his wife, Tonya, his two  
children, Jackson and Satchel,'' he said. ``God does not want me to 
be angry with anybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Besides Berkowitz, relatives of Berkowitz's victims also are  
upset about the movie, claiming it exploits the crimes for profit. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee responded only indirectly to the Times' request for comment,  
saying, ``I made a statement on that at the beginning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In May, at the Cannes film festival where ``Summer of Sam'' was  
premiered, Lee told reporters: ``I feel deeply for the parents of 
the victims of Son of Sam. At the same time, I'm an artist, and 
this is the story I wanted to tell. Even if I didn't make this 
film, that was not going to bring their daughters, their loved ones 
back. ... We do not feel that the film is a glorification of David 
Berkowitz.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Summer of Sam'' is scheduled to be released the first week of  
July. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 18:20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stewart Has Career Worth of Putts  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PINEHURST, N.C. (AP) -- Payne Stewart had already made a career's  
worth of U.S. Open putts by the time he made the one his career 
will always be remembered by. 
</P>
<P>
	He did it all without looking, just like his wife told him to  
the night before. 
</P>
<P>
	``She told me `You've got to hold your head still,''' Stewart  
said. ``I never moved my head to watch a putt go in all day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A tip from his wife, Tracey, after the third round had Stewart  
out on the practice green late Saturday, putting with his eyes 
closed. 
</P>
<P>
	He peeked just once, in time to watch the putt drop to win his  
second Open title. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I looked up it was two feet from the hole and breaking  
right to the center,'' Stewart said. ``I couldn't believe it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The magical 15-footer in a light rain won Stewart his second  
Open title. But a lot of others had to drop earlier for it to even 
matter. 
</P>
<P>
	A 25-footer on 16 to save par kept Stewart in the tournament. A  
3-footer on the next hole put him ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	Without them, the Open championship wouldn't have been at stake  
when he lined up an uphill putt he read perfectly inside the left 
edge and struck just as well as the crowds ringing the 18th green 
went berserk. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe somebody will start giving me credit for being able to  
putt,'' said Stewart, who had only 24 putts in the final round. ``I 
made a lot of them today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A bunch might be more accurate.  
</P>
<P>
	Eighteen times Stewart pulled his putter out on the slick greens  
at Pinehurst. Twelve of those times, the ball found the bottom of 
the cup. 
</P>
<P>
	But none had the drama of the last stroke at Pinehurst.  
</P>
<P>
	``I said to myself, `You've always wanted a putt to win the U.S.  
Open,''' Stewart said. ``I can't describe the feeling in my body 
when I looked up and the ball was going in the hole. It was 
unbelievable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By the time the par putt to win dropped, Stewart had used only  
three swipes of the putter on the last three of Pinehurst No. 2's 
domed greens. 
</P>
<P>
	He hit only one of those greens in regulation, but managed to  
play them 1 under. 
</P>
<P>
	``The putts Payne made on 16 and 18 showed what a great champion  
he is,'' said Phil Mickelson, who could only watch with a bemused 
look on his face as his Open chances vanished. 
</P>
<P>
	With pins tucked on ledges and leaning precariously on the  
mounded edges of Pinehurst's greens, this seemed destined to be an 
Open won by the most creative golfer around the shaved surfaces. 
</P>
<P>
	That would have been Mickelson, who used an assortment of shots  
with his lob wedge to get up-and-down on four of the first six 
holes. Or perhaps Tiger Woods, who liked to pull his 3-wood out 
around the greens to chip the ball up close. 
</P>
<P>
	But it turned out the Open would be won by the player who putted  
the best, and that was Stewart in a landslide. 
</P>
<P>
	It was quite a difference from last year at Olympic Club, where  
Stewart missed putts coming down the stretch, including one on the 
18th that would have given him a tie with Lee Janzen. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had something to prove to myself this time,'' Stewart said.  
``I had to get in position and I had to deal with it once I got 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mickelson, who one-putted four of the first six holes for par,  
missed down the stretch when it counted the most. 
</P>
<P>
	He gave himself a chance, but when his 40-footer for birdie on  
15 hit the cup, seemed ready to drop, and then spun out, his luck 
seemingly ran out. 
</P>
<P>
	Mickelson missed a 7-footer for par on 16 that dropped him into  
a tie with Stewart, then missed a 7-footer for birdie on the next 
hole. Still, even when his 25-footer slid past the cup on 18 he was 
heading toward a Monday playoff if Stewart didn't make his. 
</P>
<P>
	``His putt was a little easier than mine,'' Mickelson said. ``It  
was uphill and he could be very aggressive with it. I thought he 
had a good chance at it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Woods, for one, was glad he made it, after missing a 5-footer of  
his own on 17 that cost him the tournament. If Woods had made that 
putt, and Stewart missed on 18, there would have been a three-way 
playoff. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll be able to sleep a little better tonight,'' Woods said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
