<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Wins Cruise Control Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- An appeals court has sided with Ford Motor Co.  
in a lawsuit filed by the family of a man severely injured when his 
car went out of control and slammed into a house. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling by the 8th District Ohio Court of Appeals overturned  
Cuyahoga County Common Pleas Judge Anthony O. Calabrese Jr.'s 
decision to grant a new trial to the family of Rev. Leon Manigault. 
The 74-year-old Cleveland man was severely injured in 1993 after 
his Crown Victoria roared out of control and crashed into a 
neighbor's house. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for Manigault, who has been in a semi-comatose state  
since the accident, say cruise control caused the engines in 
certain models to accelerate rapidly. 
</P>
<P>
	Calabrese ruled that Ford had intentionally covered up data  
about cruise control in its cars. 
</P>
<P>
	But the appellate judges agreed with Ford that the original  
trial judge had been fully informed that Ford's position on sudden 
acceleration, although possibly false, made no effort to 
fraudulently conceal evidence. On Friday the judges delivered a 
24-page opinion in favor of Ford, the nation's second-largest 
automaker. 
</P>
<P>
	``The statements that Judge Calabrese made about Ford at the  
time weren't true and were something that we took offense to. We're 
glad to have this issue put behind us,'' Ford spokesman Jim Cain 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``What happened was a tragedy and we have great sympathy for  
Rev. Manigault. But the fact of the matter is, it wasn't our 
fault.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney Thomas Murray of Sandusky, who represents the  
Manigaults, said he plans to file an appeal with the Ohio Supreme 
Court. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a narrow, procedural and very technical decision that  
in no way exonerates Ford,'' Murray said. ``It hurts, but it just 
means it's going to take us a little longer.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
