<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blue Jays Give Wells New Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Left-hander David Wells, the centerpiece of the  
deal that sent Roger Clemens to the New York Yankees, agreed today 
to a contract extension that could keep him with the Toronto Blue 
Jays through the 2002 season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blue Jays picked up the $4.5-million option on Wells for  
next season and extended his deal through the 2001 and 2002 
seasons. The 2002 season will be a team option. Financial terms 
were not disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	``This solidifies where we're going and it's going to help keep  
a core together,'' Toronto president and general manager Gord Ash 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ash said the two side had been close to a deal for awhile.  
</P>
<P>
	``We talked a little bit yesterday (Saturday) and confirmed it  
(Sunday) morning but the framework of it was done a month ago 
probably,'' he said. ``It really just came down to how the dollars 
were paid out and attributed to what years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ash demurred when asked about long-term deals for young stars  
Carlos Delgado and Shawn Green. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just going to have sit back and stragetize now for a  
couple of weeks,'' Ash said. ``Those (contract talks) are not in 
the deal zone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wells, who starts today against Kansas City, is 7-5 this season  
with a 5.34 ERA. He was 18-4 last season for the Yankees, including 
a perfect game May 18 against Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	He began his career with Toronto in 1987, and has pitched for  
Detroit, Cincinnati, Baltimore and the Yankees. Wells has a career 
mark of 131-94 with 13 saves and an ERA of 4.02 in 424 games, 254 
of them starts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
