<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Failure Changed Payne Stewart  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PINEHURST, N.C. (AP) -- His father was a salesman who went out  
the front door wearing a canary yellow sportcoat some mornings on 
the theory that it was better to have a customer remember you for 
something than not at all. 
</P>
<P>
	But William Stewart never had to impress more than a half-dozen  
people at once. When his oldest son, Payne, stood over a 15-foot 
putt on the 18th green Sunday at Pinehurst No. 2 to win the U.S. 
Open, the audience was several million times that. But this time, 
it wasn't so much about inviting attention as proving he was worthy 
of it. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I looked up,'' he said, ``it was about 2 feet from the  
hole and right in the center of the cup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Failure, it turns out, changed Payne Stewart more than all his  
past success ever could. A year ago, on a shimmering Sunday at the 
Olympic Club near San Francisco, he began the final round four 
strokes clear of the field, then missed a birdie putt from that 
same 15 feet at the last hole and let the championship escape his 
grasp. 
</P>
<P>
	Olympic is nicknamed the Graveyard of Champions because the same  
thing had happened to Ben Hogan in 1955, Arnold Palmer in 1966 and 
Tom Watson in 1987. And in the way that a curse sometimes hounds 
its victims down through the years, none of the three, among the 
greatest players the game has known, ever got hold of another major 
championship. 
</P>
<P>
	When Stewart walked away from last year's disappointment, he  
vowed it wouldn't bury him. With the light fading and a steady 
drizzle falling across the Carolina sandhills, he made good on that 
promise. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I wanted to do,'' Stewart said, ``was give myself a  
chance. I never gave up. I kept plugging and I kept playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	William Stewart, a two-time Missouri State Amateur champion,  
wouldn't have settled for anything less. When Payne was younger, 
his father taught him to dance by having him stand on his shoes and 
then waltzing around the room. William died in 1985, but he willed 
his son more than good footwork, a golf game and a taste for 
outlandish clothes. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of those things came rushing back when Stewart stood in the  
house he was renting near Pinehurst on Sunday morning, getting 
ready to drive over to the course. His wife, Tracey, was in the 
next room when he turned on the TV. Since it was Father's Day, 
NBC's coverage included a brief segment about the relationship 
William and Payne Stewart shared. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just stood there and bawled in front of the television,''  
Payne remembered, ``and thought a lot about my father. I probably 
got a lot of strength from that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As it happened, he would need every ounce.  
</P>
<P>
	When Stewart won his first major championship, the 1989 PGA, it  
was cast as much the result of fortune than fortitude. The lasting 
image was of Mike Reid slumped over his putter after dropping three 
strokes to par over the last two holes -- not Stewart tearing up 
Kemper Lakes' back nine in 31 and closing with a flurry of birdies. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, too, his first U.S. Open win, at Hazeltine in 1991, had  
the feel of a man in the right place at the right time. Twice, 
eventual loser Scott Simpson let Stewart climb out of a two-stroke 
ditch over the final three holes -- first to earn a shot at the 
playoff on Sunday, then again to win the national championship. 
</P>
<P>
	But there were no questions left by the end of this one.  
</P>
<P>
	Stewart began the day at 1-under-par, one stroke ahead of Phil  
Mickelson and two ahead of Tiger Woods. Another stroke back was 
David Duval and Vijay Singh. Stewart knew one or two of them might 
flinch over the course of the afternoon on a layout as tough as 
this one. But he also knew he was going to have beat one or all of 
them himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Ultimately, it was Mickelson, about to become a father himself,  
who pushed Stewart the hardest. 
</P>
<P>
	Twice on the back nine, the left-hander wrested the lead away.  
But he gave it back the final time at the 191-yard, par-3 17th. 
There, Mickelson hit his tee shot to 8 feet and Stewart to about 
half that distance. Mickelson missed his birdie try and Stewart 
made his, setting up the final act. 
</P>
<P>
	On 18, Stewart dumped his drive into the right rough, hacked it  
out with a 9-iron and then hit a lob wedge to 15 feet. Mickelson 
took the more conventional Open route -- hit the fairway, hit the 
green -- to 25 feet. Again, this time much more improbably, he 
missed and Stewart made. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would have made a cool story for my daughter to read  
about,'' Mickelson said, ``but it's still something special.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Exactly how special Mickelson may not realize until he's  
actually raised a family of his own. 
</P>
<P>
	But Stewart had no problem remembering the feeling when someone  
asked him whether this victory would supplant his first win out on 
Tour -- the 1982 Quad City Classic -- as his most cherished memory. 
</P>
<P>
	``That will never change,'' Stewart said, ``because my dad was  
there to see it.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@ap.org. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
