<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 23:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Falwell Paper Knocks Concert Name </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROANOKE, Va. (AP) -- The Rev. Jerry Falwell's newspaper has  
turned its attention from warning about Tinky Winky to the 
``demonic legend'' behind the female music tour called Lilith Fair. 
</P>
<P>
	Lilith Fair was created in 1997 by singer-songwriter Sarah  
McLachlan. More than 800,000 people attended the summer concert 
series last year. The third and final tour begins July 8 and 
features diverse artists such as Sheryl Crow, The Dixie Chicks and 
Queen Latifah. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many young people no doubt attend the Lilith Fair concerts not  
knowing the demonic legend of the mystical woman whose name the 
series manifests,'' an editor of National Liberty Journal wrote in 
the Parents Alert column of the June issue. 
</P>
<P>
	According to ancient Jewish literature, Lilith was created by  
God as Adam's first wife, but left Eden after refusing to be 
submissive to Adam. Lilith Fair got its name from the original 
aspect of the mystical character, a woman seeking equality and 
independence, tour publicist Ambrosia Healy said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The article in Falwell's conservative Christian newspaper,  
headlined, ``Secrets of the Lilith Fair,'' points out that there 
are many conflicting accounts of the Lilith character, and then 
outlines the darker aspects. 
</P>
<P>
	``According to pagan legend,'' the article said, Lilith dwelled  
with the demons of the earth after leaving Eden and went mad after 
witnessing the execution of her children. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a result, she went on a killing spree, seducing and  
murdering her own demonic male offspring and then slaying their 
children,'' the article said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. McLachlan said when she started the all-female tour that it  
was an effort to promote women's equality and not ``a soapbox for 
extreme feminism. It isn't about dissing men. I just think 
everybody is equal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Falwell was ridiculed after the Parents Alert column in February  
cited evidence that the creators of the ``Teletubbies'' show 
intended Tinky Winky to be a gay role model. 
</P>
<P>
	``This Lilith Fair alert is certain to draw more fire, but we  
are willing to take the heat in order to document the truth behind 
the benign appearance of this music festival,'' the article by 
senior editor J.M. Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Falwell spokeswoman Beth Bragg said the Lynchburg  
minister had not read the article in the newspaper in which he is 
listed as editor and publisher, and declined to comment. 
</P>
<P>
	``But he has the highest regard and confidence in his editor,''  
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. McLachlan's manager, Terry McBride, said Lilith Fair simply  
celebrates women in music. ``To say that Lilith Fair is, in fact, a 
pagan event is ignoring the actual facts and trying to create a 
spin to it,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 20:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Computer Bug Forced E-Mail Shutdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The latest computer virus, a reminder that  
technology has its drawbacks, was also a throwback to simpler times 
-- perhaps two or three years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if it didn't actually infect the machines on their  
desktops, the outbreak of a file-devouring scourge named 
Worm.Explore.Zip affected millions of computer users over the past 
two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	For hours or days, many companies and other organizations were  
forced to shut down their e-mail systems and computer networks to 
be disinfected or immunized. Suddenly, there was no way to dash off 
a one-line note to a co-worker across the room or across the 
continent. Suddenly, people needed to get reaquainted with quaint 
old ways of doing business. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all had to remember how to pick up a telephone and talk,''  
said Dave Suffia, a spokesman for airplane maker Boeing Co., which 
was forced on June 11 to shut down an infected e-mail system 
serving 160,000 employee accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	While hardly the most hi-tech aspects of the Internet  
revolution, e-mail and smaller-network features like instant 
messaging have become as second nature to many people as dial tones 
and light bulbs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's amazing how quickly a lot of us became so absolutely  
dependent on e-mail,'' said Suffia, estimating that as many as 
900,000 e-mails are sent by Boeing employees every day and that 2.1 
million are received. ``We're now dependent on this as a work tool, 
a social tool.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So when their e-mail systems went dark while systems managers  
were doing battle with the computer virus, many people didn't know 
what to do with themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	At the New York offices of Ericsson, the Swedish manaufacturer  
of cellular phones and other telecommunications equipment, people 
busied themselves by cleaning their desks and making coffee. 
</P>
<P>
	In some cases, the response to the network outages caused by the  
Worm.Explore.Zip outbreak wasn't much different from the way people 
might react to a power outage or, back in grade school days, a snow 
storm. 
</P>
<P>
	Hopeful about rumors that employees were being sent home at  
other companies, some workers for defense contractor Lockheed 
Martin called in to ask, ``'Are we going home early? Are we closing 
the facility?,''' said Elaine Hinsdale, manager of communications 
and public affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	While the current e-mail system at Lockheed is just one year  
old, with about 111,000 users and 1 million messages transmitted 
each day, it ``has become a key tool in the way we conduct 
business,'' said Hinsdale. 
</P>
<P>
	So when Lockheed's employees lost e-mail service while the  
system was taken off line from late afternoon on June 10 until the 
morning of June 11, Hinsdale's office had to ``remind them there 
were other means of conducting business a couple of years ago 
before you had e-mail.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 19:10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cops Shoot Runaway Bull on NY Street </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A bull escaped from an illegal rodeo and  
rampaged through city streets, at times charging at people, before 
police officers shot it dead on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Detective Robert Samuel, a police spokesman, said the bull was  
one of nine owned by a North Carolina-based rodeo company that 
hired a vacant lot in the New York borough of Queens for a show, 
but was ordered to shut down for lacking a permit. 
</P>
<P>
	As police watched rodeo workers loading the animals on a truck,  
one of them bolted. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess he didn't want to go,'' Samuel said.  
</P>
<P>
	The animal rumbled several blocks through the neighborhood,  
pursued by cops and a rodeo worker with a lariat, who tried in vain 
to lasso it. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, officers tried to herd the bull into a parking lot, but  
it refused to cooperate and was shot dead after the police deemed 
it a menace to the public. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
