<DOCNO> APW19990620.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 20:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Women's World Cup Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	There was no record crowd Sunday for the Women's World Cup  
doubleheader at Foxboro Stadium. Of course, there was no scheduled 
appearance by the U.S. team, either. 
</P>
<P>
	The attendance at Foxboro was 14,873, with a walk-up sale of  
1,292 on gameday. The crowd came to see Australia-Ghana and 
Norway-Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Organizers were encouraged, considering that the Red Sox were at  
home, the U.S. Open was on television and it was a nice day for the 
beach. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think it's a very solid crowd for the second day of the  
tournament, the first day of the tournament here at Foxboro with 
four teams that don't really have a very strong fan base in the 
area,'' said Richard Finn, Women's World Cup director of public 
reltations. ``We think it's nothing to be disappointed with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also noted that the total crowd for Saturday in San Jose and  
the Meadowlands and today at Foxboro came to 117,143, more than the 
estimated 112,000 who attended the entire 1995 Women's World Cup in 
Sweden. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SEEING RED:* Ghana received four yellow cards and a red card in  
its 1-1 tie with Australia, which got just one yellow card. 
</P>
<P>
	``I cannot comment on the refereeing, but I thought that the  
slightest attention drew a card,'' Ghana coach Emmanuel Afranie 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ghana played with 10 players after losing Barikiso Tettey-Quao  
to the first red card of the tournament in the 25th minute when she 
tackled Joanne Peters from behind. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ghana is noted for that type of play,'' Australia goalie  
Tracey Wheeler said. ``It reminded me of the men's World Cup. I 
think the red card set a standard for how this tournament will be 
played.'' 
</P>
<P>
	FIFA spokesman Keith Cooper stressed before the tournament that  
the organization would make it clear to the teams that referees 
will not allow excessive physical activity. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *HAT TRICKS:* When Brazil's Sissi scored her third goal of  
Saturday's rout of Mexico, teammate Pretinha knew what she had to 
do. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got my third goal because I was jealous that Sissi scored  
three,'' Pretinha said with a laugh after the 7-1 victory in the 
World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Pretinha, a diminutive forward with an exceptional burst to the  
ball, scored early and late. She needed only 2 minutes, 10 seconds 
to get her first and had her second through 12 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	But then Sissi got her hat trick, including two on free kicks.  
</P>
<P>
	In the 90th minute, however, Pretinha got her head on a cross  
for her third score. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was thinking that I had to get three to match Sissi,'' she  
said. ``I was very fortunate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pretinha and Sissi got their hat tricks at Giants Stadium in  
front of the greatest of all Brazilian players, Pele, who was in 
the stands. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SURPRISE GOALIE:* Australia's Tracey Wheeler found out just  
Sunday morning she would be the starting goalkeeper against Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Belinda Kitching played in the last three games of the Oceania  
World Cup qualifying tournament last October and all three in the 
Australia Cup in January. Australia won five of those games and 
tied one. But Wheeler, 31, is more experienced, having played three 
games -- all losses -- in the 1995 World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Greg Brown said ``both goalies played two games each (in  
tuneups for the tournament). Kitching also had a sore hand. Wheeler 
did an all right job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a surprise for me to start,'' Wheeler said after the  
1-1 tie. ``Up until a few months ago I was the No. 3 goalkeeper on 
the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TEEN TEAM:* It might have been beaten 7-1 by Brazil on  
Saturday, but the Mexican team still has its future ahead of it. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mexican girls can still dream of World Cups to come. Of the  
Mexican starters, only Andrea Rodebaugh is over 22. Four of the 
starters are teen-agers and a total of seven are 20 or under. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil's team is older and much more experienced: the star  
scorers are Sissi (32) and Pretinha (23). 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 20:21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
