<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oakwood Homes Eyes Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) -- Oakwood Homes Corp. says it is looking  
for a possible suitor after a series of difficult financial periods 
capped with an announcement that quarterly earnings may be only 
half of Wall Street's expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	Oakwood, the country's largest retailer and third-largest  
builder of manufactured homes, cited soft sales in retail and 
wholesale markets in warning third-quarter income could fall as 
much as 50 percent below analysts' projections. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although business in March showed signs of improvement over  
the prior year, sales during the current quarter have exhibited 
unexpected weakness,'' Nicholas St. George, chairman and chief 
executive, said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The Greensboro-based company announced Friday its board of  
directors has hired Merrill, Lynch &AMP; Co. to explore the possibility 
of a sale or merger, including a management-led buyout. 
</P>
<P>
	``The board is exploring strategic alternatives. We are in a  
quiet period,'' said Jo Andrews, an Oakwood spokeswoman. ``It's not 
appropriate to comment further.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street analysts had been expecting a quarterly profit of 55  
cents a share, according to a survey by First Call Corp. The 
earnings report will be release July 28. 
</P>
<P>
	It would be the sixth consecutive quarter of disappointing  
earnings reports for Oakwood, which earned $55.4 million on $1.5 
billion in sales last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Same-store sales from April through May also were 10 percent  
lower compared to the year-ago period, Oakwood said. 
</P>
<P>
	Company stock tumbled 75 percent last year after Oakwood took  
$45 million in charges against earnings because more people 
defaulted on its mortgage loans than expected and more people than 
anticipated refinanced their loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Though shipments for the industry this year are rising, they are  
doing so more slowly than last year, according to the Manufactured 
Housing Institute. Through April, shipments were up 3 percent from 
the same period a year ago, compared with a gain of 4.4 percent in 
the first four months of 1998, according to the trade group. 
</P>
<P>
	Oakwood, which employs 12,500 people, owns 388 stores across the  
U.S. and produces manufactured homes in 32 plants. It also sells 
through independent dealers. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
