<DOCNO> APW19990620.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 11:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stars Savor Individual Triumphs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Now that the Dallas Stars have won the Stanley Cup  
with a style that relied heavily on a team concept, they can begin 
savoring what it means to them individually. 
</P>
<P>
	For Ed Belfour, Brett Hull and Mike Modano, the title is  
vindication. Each can shed their tainted reputations for a new 
identity: NHL champions. 
</P>
<P>
	For 39-year-old Guy Carbonneau, 38-year-old Craig Ludwig and  
36-year-old Brian Skrudland, former Cup winners who've kept playing 
to relive the satisfaction, victory feels even better than they 
remembered. 
</P>
<P>
	And for grinders Derian Hatcher and Pat Verbeek, knowing their  
name will forever be engraved on their sport's most cherished 
trophy is affirmation that all the lumps and bruises were worth it. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a special, magical group that will never be  
repeated,'' coach Ken Hitchcock said early Sunday following a 2-1 
triple-overtime victory over the Buffalo Sabres that secured a 4-2 
series win. 
</P>
<P>
	``We may have more talented teams or more skilled teams, but  
we'll never be as tight as this group.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars were the best regular-season team the past two years  
and if they didn't win critics would've said they peaked too soon. 
</P>
<P>
	But winning the Presidents' Trophy came in handy when Game 7 of  
the Western Conference finals between top-seeded Dallas and 
second-seeded Colorado was played at Reunion Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Sabres learned the Stars still had plenty of energy and  
passion left as they rallied from a loss in the opener, then won 
two straight games after being tied 2-2. 
</P>
<P>
	In their sixth season in Dallas, the franchise that began as the  
Minnesota North Stars ended a 32-year wait for the organization's 
first title, the longest in NHL history. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars also became the league's first champions from the Sun  
Belt -- a concept hockey fans never could've imagined when the '90s 
began. 
</P>
<P>
	A look at some of the people who made it possible and what it  
took to do it: 
</P>
<P>
	--Belfour had played more postseason games (107) without winning  
a championship than any goaltender in league history, which led to 
the knock that he cracks under pressure. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``Eagle'' soared this postseason, maintaining his cool  
during a 16-7 championship run that included two triple-overtime 
victories. 
</P>
<P>
	``I stayed focused and I stayed strong,'' said Belfour, who  
outplayed Patrick Roy in the Western finals and was at least the 
equal of Dominik Hasek in the finals. 
</P>
<P>
	The championship also saved Belfour's job, as Dallas will look  
to trade promising backup Roman Turek rather than expose him in the 
upcoming expansion draft. 
</P>
<P>
	--Joe Nieuwendyk's absence from the playoffs last year left  
Dallas a scorer away from challenging Detroit in the conference 
finals. Now they really know what they were missing as he led the 
playoffs with 11 goals, including a record-tying six game-winners. 
</P>
<P>
	He was voted postseason MVP for the second time, a decade after  
leading Calgary to the Cup. The Flyers traded him to Dallas because 
they thought he was too fragile; overcoming operations on both 
knees and enduring a grueling rehabilitation that sidelined him 
early this season proved he's not. 
</P>
<P>
	--Hull was brought in to be a postseason sharpshooter and he was,  
scoring the cup-winning goal in the third overtime early Sunday and 
knocking in the game-winner in Game 2. He did it all despite groin 
and knee injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	--Modano has shed the pretty-boy image that's hung over him his  
entire career. No one played better the last two games and he did 
it despite a broken wrist. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ludwig and Skrudland, teammates on the 1986 Cup-winning  
Montreal Canadiens, went 13 years between titles, the longest span 
in league history. 
</P>
<P>
	--Mike Keane, whose two goals in Game 7 of the conference finals  
ousted his former Colorado teammates, became the ninth player to 
win titles with three clubs. Next up for Keane is getting this Cup 
tattooed on his ankle next to ink images of the trophies he won 
with Colorado in 1996 and Montreal in '93. Carbonneau, the league's 
oldest player this season, also won his third title. 
</P>
<P>
	--Benoit Hogue missed three weeks with two torn knee ligaments,  
then played the final two games. By delaying surgery, he risked 
further injury and guaranteed he won't be ready for the start of 
next season, which will make it tough for the free agent to find a 
job. 
</P>
<P>
	--General manager Bob Gainey, who won five Stanley Cups in his  
Hall of Fame career, put the team together in his own image. 
Third-year owner Tom Hicks opened his checkbook to let him do it. 
</P>
<P>
	--Hitchcock, a successful coach in midgets and juniors for 16  
years who didn't get a shot at the NHL until slimming down from 478 
pounds, pushed, pulled and laid off his players at all the right 
times to get the most out of the second-oldest team (30.6 years) 
ever to win an NHL title. Toronto in 1967 averaged 31.4. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you see the absolute joy and the raw emotions of the  
players, it's unbelievable,'' Hitchcock said. ``You appreciate what 
it takes to get here.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 16:40:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Finals Ratings Falling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- NBC is finally feeling the effect of the  
post-Michael Jordan era, with its lowest ratings ever in the NBA 
Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	After the lowest Game 1 rating in 13 years, NBC posted a 10.0  
preliminary rating for Game 2 between the New York Knicks and San 
Antonio Spurs on Friday night, the network said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The overnight rating represents 64 percent of the country. The  
national rating will be released Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 10.0 rating was 44 percent lower than last year's Game 2,  
between Jordan's Chicago Bulls and the Utah Jazz, and 21 percent 
lower than the second game in 1994 between the Knicks and Houston 
Rockets. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1994 final (12.4 rating), the last season to be played  
entirely without Jordan, was NBC's lowest rated in its eight years 
of showing the NBA. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, after basically a decade of the greatest athlete of  
this generation, we're due for a building year,'' NBC Sports 
chairman Dick Ebersol said, ``and this may be ours. 
</P>
<P>
	``My thought was we'd be off 25-30 percent. When it's all over,  
if it goes six games we'll be right there. If it's a four-game 
sweep, we'll be lower.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The combination of Jordan's retirement, the lockout, two  
uncompetitive games and ugly basketball, have kept viewers away. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC was helped by competitive six-game series the last two years  
and the speculation that Jordan could retire. Six of the eight 
highest-rated finals involved Jordan's Bulls. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, the network has San Antonio, the smallest market in  
the NBA, and a banged-up Knicks team playing without Patrick Ewing 
and with a hobbling Larry Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not a medic unit,'' Ebersol said. ``We can't deal with  
the injuries of Ewing and Johnson. We'll wish for a competitive 
game to put us back in line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ebersol says the network won't have to give make-good spots to  
advertisers who were expecting higher ratings because of 
better-than-expected numbers in the regular season and earlier 
playoff rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox was forced to provide extra spots after the World Series,  
which was a four-game sweep and the lowest-rated ever. 
</P>
<P>
	``We so over performed our guarantees for the regular season and  
earlier rounds that we have no problems,'' Ebersol said. ``We just 
have the problem of any series, we want more than four games. 
That's up to the gods.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NBC's ratings were 16 percent lower for the first three rounds  
of the playoffs and 7 percent lower in the regular season. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
