<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7:30 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO, KLA Agree on Demilitarization  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO and the Kosovo Liberation Army  
early Monday signed an accord providing for the demilitarization of 
the KLA, effectively ending its existence as a military force. The 
pact was signed after midnight by British Lt. Gen. Mike Jackson, 
head of alliance forces in Kosovo, and Hashim Thaci, political head 
of the KLA. The signing occurred less than half an hour after the 
final deadline for the pullout of Serb forces from Kosovo, which 
was Sunday at midnight. Determining the future of the rebel army 
had been considered a crucial element of the Kosovo peace plan. 

</P>
<P>
	Experts Examine Alleged Atrocities  
</P>
<P>
	VELIKA KRUSA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- British forensic experts today  
started gingerly probing a burned-out house said to contain the 
charred remains of ethnic Albanian massacre victims. It is among 
the first alleged atrocity sites in Kosovo chosen for scrutiny by 
the International War Crimes Tribunal. Velika Krusa was one of the 
towns cited in the indictment of Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic. According to Mihidin Duraku, who owns the house, Serbs 
in police uniforms trucked in about 40 people on March 26, marched 
them into the house, shot them and set fire to the building. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Wants Tougher Gun Show Laws  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton appealed today from Europe  
for the House to reverse course and impose tougher controls on gun 
show sales. Top congressional Democrats looked to use the issue to 
the party's advantage in next year's elections. Clinton repeated an 
appeal, made in his weekly radio address taped yesterday, that 
lawmakers approve background checks on gun sales at flea markets 
and gun shows. The president said no one seriously has questioned 
``there would be fewer improper sales and we would make America 
safer'' if lawmakers approved those checks. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton To Live in Ark., NY  
</P>
<P>
	COLOGNE, Germany (AP) -- President Clinton said today that he  
plans to divide his post-presidential time between Arkansas and New 
York and will work hard on issues he cares about -- since he's not 
good enough at golf to become a professional. He and Mrs. Clinton, 
shortly after settling in at the White House, agreed they would 
move to New York when his time in office ended, Clinton said. ``I 
would divide my time between New York and going home to Arkansas, 
and finishing my library and doing my work there,'' he said. 

</P>
<P>
	PLO Seeks End To U.S. Restrictions  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Palestinians will ask the United States to  
repeal laws restricting U.S. dealings with the PLO, a senior 
Palestinian official said today. The Palestinians will make the 
proposal Wednesday when the U.S.-Palestinian bilateral committees 
meet in the West Bank town of Ramallah, Palestinian Minister of 
Planning Nabil Shaath told The Associated Press. Laws the 
Palestinians want repealed include one requiring the PLO to 
periodically apply for permission to run an office in Washington. 

</P>
<P>
	Saddam Among Richest Leaders  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Saddam Hussein is worth more than Queen  
Elizabeth, according to Forbes' list of billionaires released 
today. The Iraqi leader, with an estimated wealth of $6 billion, is 
No. 6 on the magazine's list of ``The Nonworking Rich: Kings, 
Queens and Dictators,'' a companion to its annual ranking of the 
world's wealthiest people. The British queen is No. 10. The 
magazine attributed Hussein's wealth to oil and to an alleged 
smuggling operation controlled by his son Odai. 

</P>
<P>
	Stewart Wins Dramatic U.S. Open  
</P>
<P>
	PINEHURST, N.C. (AP) -- Motivated by past failures and haunted by  
bizarre breaks that always seemed to go the other way, Payne 
Stewart made a 20-foot par putt on the 18th hole today at storied 
Pinehurst No. 2 to win the U.S. Open by one stroke over Phil 
Mickelson. In the most dramatic U.S. Open of the decade, Stewart 
showed the mettle and patience required of its champion. One stroke 
behind with three holes to play, he made a 25-foot putt for par to 
catch Mickelson, a 5-foot birdie putt on the 17th to take the lead, 
and then his 24th putt of the day to win the Open. 

</P>
<P>
	Dodgers Defeat Phillies 3-2  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Kevin Brown retired 17 consecutive batters  
and made a timely tag at home plate to preserve an eighth-inning 
lead today as the Los Angeles Dodgers defeated the Philadelphia 
Phillies 3-2. Eric Karros hit two solo home runs for the Dodgers, 
who have won two straight after losing nine of 11. Brown (8-4) 
hardly looked as though he would be around for long when he 
stumbled through the first inning, giving up two runs. But he 
settled down in a 10-pitch second after a 33-pitch first. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief By ANDREW DAMPF  
  	   	
</P>
