<HEADLINE> Protesters Gather Outside Fagan Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Carrying signs saying ``Happy  
Kidnapper's Day'' and ``Know the Truth,'' about two dozen people 
gathered Sunday outside the home of kidnapper Stephen Fagan to 
decry his jail-free sentence and urge his daughters to reconcile 
with their mother. 
</P>
<P>
	Fagan, 57, was spared a trial when he pleaded guilty in  
Massachusetts last month to kidnapping his daughters 20 years ago. 
He received five years of probation and was ordered to perform 
2,000 hours of community service. 
</P>
<P>
	Fagan, who used fake names and social security numbers and  
reinvented himself as a socialite named Dr. William Martin in Palm 
Beach, could have faced 20 years in prison if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Several protesters Sunday had personal stories similar to the  
Fagan saga, talking about children being abducted by desperate 
parents in the midst of custody battles. 
</P>
<P>
	Fagan and his family appeared to be away for the weekend. The  
oceanfront of the two-story Mediterranean house, placed on the 
market last week for $3.5 million, were shuttered as if expecting a 
hurricane. 
</P>
<P>
	Fagan's daughters, 25-year-old Rachael Martin and 22-year-old  
Lisa Martin, have stood firmly behind their father and have not 
made any effort to contact their mother. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 19:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tiger Woods Knocked Out by Two Putts  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PINEHURST, N.C. (AP) -- Tiger Woods is confident he'll win  
another major championship some day. It didn't happen at the U.S. 
Open because of two short putts that got away. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods, still seeking another major to add to his record-breaking  
victory at the 1997 Masters, finished two shots behind winner Payne 
Stewart on Sunday after missing a 2 1/2-footer at No. 11 and a 
5-footer at 17. 
</P>
<P>
	If both putts go in, Woods is teeing up with Stewart in an  
18-hole playoff Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hung in there with my short game and did everything I  
possibly could to hang in there and give myself a chance,'' said 
Woods, who shot an even-par 70 to finish 1 over for the tournament. 
``I'm very pleased with my performance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He fell three shots off the lead with his bogey at the 453-yard  
11th, pulling the near-gimme putt past the cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eleven was a putt I should have made,'' Woods said. ``But if  
you look at my entire week, I made a lot of putts to save myself. A 
lot of putts from 15 feet in just for pars, and without those I 
wouldn't have been in the position I was coming down the stretch to 
win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two of Woods' best putts came after his miss at 11.  
</P>
<P>
	He rolled in a 20-footer for birdie on the 14th, kneeling to the  
ground and pumping his right fist when the ball fell from sight. 
Two holes later, he made a marvelous second shot to set up a 
15-foot putt. When that one dropped, too -- only the 11th birdie all 
week at the second toughest hole on the course -- his fist cut 
through the air even harder. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods put his tee shot at the par-3 17th into a bunker, then  
tried to save himself with his sand wedge. The shot rolled past the 
hole and seemed to stop no more than 5 feet away, though Woods 
insisted he had at least an 8-footer. 
</P>
<P>
	Either way, the putt spun out of the cup, forcing him to tap in  
for a bogey that ended his chance of winning. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was short, but not that short,'' he said. ``It's very easy  
to miss that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With one more chance to make up ground, Woods lined up a  
35-footer as the bells from a nearby church were ringing. He could 
have used a little divine intervention when the ball slid past the 
left side of hole. 
</P>
<P>
	A few minutes later, the noise at 18 was deafening when Stewart  
made a 15-footer to save par and clinch a one-shot victory over 
Phil Mickelson. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was hoping he was going to make it,'' Woods said. ``I can  
sleep a little better tonight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He complained that officials from the U.S. Golf Association  
pulled out their stopwatches and threatened the final groups -- 
Woods-Tim Herron and Stewart-Mickelson -- with a one-shot penalty 
for slow play. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods said the decision was disruptive and unnecessary during a  
major championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the greens as severe as they are ... it takes time to  
figure out the slopes,'' he said. ``I understand the pace-of-play 
rule, but there are exceptions to it. And by looking as these 
greens, I think that's a pretty good exception.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All in all, though, Woods was upbeat about tying for third in  
the U.S. Open at age 23. 
</P>
<P>
	``It makes me feel I can definitely win,'' he said. ``I know I  
have the game, I have the mind for it and it's just a matter of 
time.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
