<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria 2, North Korea 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- Mercy Akide, whose flashy style proved a  
crowd-pleaser at the Rose Bowl, scored once and assisted on the 
go-ahead goal Sunday night as Nigeria opened women's World Cup play 
with a 2-1 victory over North Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory gave added credibility to the Nigerians as a  
contender in Group A, which includes the United States. The 
Americans face Nigeria on Thursday in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Akide, who put Nigeria ahead in the 50th minute, fed Rita  
Nwadike for a goal to snap a 1-1 tie in the 79th minute. 
</P>
<P>
	Taking a pass on the right wing, Akide dribbled toward the right  
post -- near the spot she scored from earlier -- and passed the ball 
across the mouth of the goal. Nwadike had only to slam the ball 
into the net. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight minutes earlier, Song Ok Jo had tied it for North Korea,  
kicking in a hard crossing pass from Jong Ran Jo. 
</P>
<P>
	Akide's earlier goal came on a shot from a difficult angle near  
the goal line, with the ball slipping through the hands of 
goaltender Yong Sun Kye. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd of 17,102, less than one-fifth the Rose Bowl's  
capacity, was considerably more lively for the North Korea-Nigeria 
match than it was during the match that preceded it, a 1-1 tie 
between Germany and Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	Contributing to the atmosphere during the second match was a  
drum-playing contingent of some 200 Nigerian fans, many wearing 
green robes and hats. There also was a smaller group of fans 
cheering for North Korea and waving that country's flag. 
</P>
<P>
	Akide, who is extremely quick and has some dazzling moves with  
the ball, scored 10 of Nigeria's 28 goals in qualifying rounds as 
her country continued to dominate the women's game in Africa, where 
the team has not lost to an opponent from the continent in 10 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	The North Koreans came into the World Cup as one of the  
tournament's mystery teams, although they showed they were 
competitive by playing China close in the finals of Asian Cup and 
Asian Games, losing 1-0 both times. 
</P>
<P>
	In Sunday's other two games, at Foxboro, Mass., Norway defeated  
Russia 2-1, and Australia and Ghana played to a 1-1 tie. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
