<HEADLINE> Dudley Mulls Left-Handed Free Throws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- New York Knicks center Chris Dudley, who doesn't  
shoot free throws very well right-handed, might try them 
left-handed in Monday night's Game 3 of the NBA Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``It depends on how his elbow feels. He can't always extend it  
all the way,'' assistant coach Brendan Malone said after working 
with Dudley practicing free throws left-handed at the conclusion of 
the Knicks' practice Sunday at Madison Square Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	Dudley, a 46 percent career free throw shooter, made five in a  
row at one point and four in a row at another while practicing 
left-handed. He also missed quite a few. 
</P>
<P>
	Dudley said he had never attempted a free throw left-handed  
until Friday morning's shootaround, when his hyperextended right 
elbow was causing him too much pain. 
</P>
<P>
	``By game time I was able to shoot righty,'' said Dudley, who  
did not attempt a free throw and went 0-for-2 from the field in 
Game 2. 
  	   	
</P>
