<HEADLINE> Frenchman Leads Swiss Cycling Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEIRINGEN, Switzerland (AP) -- Frenchman Laurent Jalabert showed  
his fatigue Sunday but still managed to retake the lead in the Tour 
De Suisse. 
</P>
<P>
	Jalabert, who had been leading the race since the start, lost  
the jersey to Gilberto Simoni on Saturday's arduous mountain stage, 
where he had to chase down the Simoni and Francesco Casagrande in 
the closing miles. 
</P>
<P>
	He was widely expected to retake the lead with ease in the time  
trial, but struggled throughout to finish eighth, one minute and 25 
seconds behind Russian Vjatceslave Ekimov, the stage winner. 
</P>
<P>
	However he still managed to make up enough time on Simoni to go  
ahead overall by just two seconds. Casagrande lies third, 12 
seconds behind Jalabert. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking to Swiss television after the race, Jalabert admitted  
that he had been tired after Saturday's stage. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will try to keep the jersey for as long as possible, but  
there are two difficult stages to come. We'll see,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Five riders are within a minute of the Frenchman in the overall  
standings. On Monday, the riders leave Switzerland for the first 
time in this year's race, with a 101-mile stage to Maurens, 
Liechtenstein. 
  	   	
</P>
