<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres' Playoff Eun Ends With a Thud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Scott Norwood's missed field goal hurt, but  
the goal that cost Buffalo the Stanley Cup caused an even deeper 
wound as the Sabres argued it wasn't even a legal shot. 
</P>
<P>
	Brett Hull's goal near the end of the third overtime Sunday  
morning gave Dallas a 2-1 victory to win the NHL finals series 4-2. 
</P>
<P>
	While Dallas celebrated, Buffalo was left to confront what coach  
Lindy Ruff termed ``our worst nightmare.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo lost four Super Bowl games, including one when Norwood  
was wide right with a last-second, game-winning field goal. At 
least that play was legal, which some of the Sabres insisted wasn't 
the case with Hull's goal. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Bryan Lewis, the NHL's chief referee, Hull's goal  
counted because he didn't lose control of the puck as his skate 
entered the crease in front of Buffalo goalie Dominik Hasek. 
</P>
<P>
	A player is not allowed to enter the crease without the puck,  
and therein lies the difference in interpretation. 
</P>
<P>
	``It went off Dom's glove and it went off (Brian) Holzinger's  
skate,'' Ruff said. ``It went outside the crease and his (Hull) 
foot is in the crease when he scores the goal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that was the worst-case scenario,'' Ruff said. ``An  
overtime game where pandemonium sets in and they can't take it 
back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some Sabres couldn't understand why Hull's goal was allowed to  
stand. Others accepted it. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Juneau, who sank the Sabres in the 1998 Eastern Conference  
finals with a goal for the Washington Capitals, claimed the league 
lost its nerve amid the sudden storm of celebration. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a gutless move,'' Juneau said. ``If we had scored a  
goal like that, it would have been called back. Because it was a 
goal that gave them the Stanley Cup, everybody jumped on the ice 
and they were afraid to make the call.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I haven't seen it,'' Sabres captain Michael Peca said. ``I  
don't know if I want to. We got some sort of cockamamie explanation 
but it's a situation now where we don't want to whine about it. 
It's out of our hands. It was a great game, and we don't want to 
take away from that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek and Dallas goalie Ed Belfour were brilliant in facing 104  
shots in 114 minutes, 51 seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	The game ended about 1:30 a.m., nearly six hours after it began.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing left, I'll tell you that,'' Sabres forward  
Dixon Ward said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be unfair to Dallas for this to turn into a  
controversial goal,'' Ward said. ``It would be unfair to Brett 
Hull, who's worked 15 years to get a Stanley Cup. It's a stupid 
rule anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the NHL's fault for having a stupid rule, so they can  
deal with it,'' Ward said. ``We're not going to worry about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added Peca: ``We believed that we could beat the Dallas Stars  
and a couple of bounces could have made a difference for us, but 
they played very well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres' run from the No. 7 seed in the Eastern Conference to  
the Stanley Cup finals did not surprise the Dallas Stars. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to realize that this is not a seventh-seeded team,''  
Stars center Mike Modano said. ``They were one of the top two or 
three teams the whole year. They played a spectacular game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This was as good as we could play,'' Ward said. ``They were  
just a little bit better. We can't sit here and say we should have 
done this or we should have done that, because we did everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Juneau added, ``I believe everybody will remember this as  
the Stanley Cup that was never won. It was given to a good team, 
but the goal was not a legal goal.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 21:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Islanders Trade Palffy to LA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNIONDALE, N.Y. (AP) -- After many attempts to cut star right  
wing Ziggy Palffy's salary from its dwindling payroll, the New York 
Islanders were finally successful Sunday night, sending Palffy to 
the Los Angeles Kings as part of an eight-player trade. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Palffy, the Islanders sent center Bryan  
Smolinski, goaltender Marcel Cousineau and New Jersey's 
fourth-round pick in the 1999 Entry Draft to the Kings. In return, 
New York gets center Olli Jokinen, left wing Josh Green, defenseman 
Mathieu Biron and the Kings' first pick (eighth overall) in the 
upcoming Entry Draft. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're very pleased to be able to add this kind of offense to  
the team,'' Dave Taylor, the Kings' senior vice-president and 
general manager said in a conference call in Los Angeles. ``I think 
L.A. is going to love him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Palffy, who was the Islanders' leading scorer this past season  
with 22 goals and 28 assists in 50 games, was deemed expendable 
with a contract that has four more years and $24 million to be 
paid. He signed the contract last Dec. 17, and missed 32 games as a 
restricted free agent. In his last three full seasons, Palffy 
scored 136 goals. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a marquee player, one of the most exciting players in the  
game,'' Taylor said. ``Every time he touches the puck he does 
something exciting. He's very creative.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor said the Kings had been talking with Palffy for at least  
a year, since the last contract dispute with the Islanders. He said 
the trade represent a $6 million increase in the Kings' payroll. 
</P>
<P>
	``Management has given us a lot of support on this,'' he said.  
``I don't think there are many teams in the NHL that would be able 
to take on an additional $6 million in annual salary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smolinski was a disappointment this past season with only 16  
goals and 24 assists in 82 games. Cousineau saw action in six games 
and went 0-4-0 with a 2.87 goals-against average. The pick the 
Islanders traded away was acquired from the Devils in the deal this 
season for forward Sergei Nemchinov. 
</P>
<P>
	Jokinen, in his first full season with Los Angeles, had nine  
goals and 12 assists in 66 games. Biron played for Shawinigan in 
junior hockey. Both players were No. 1 draft pick of the Kings -- 
Jokinen, the third overall in 1997 and Biron No. 21 in 1998. Green 
played in 27 games for the Kings last season and had one goal and 
three assists. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never want to trade a player as special as Ziggy but we  
are very happy to get a collection of talented young players and 
our third top 10 pick in return,'' Islanders general manager Mike 
Milbury said. ``We believe Jokinen will immediately become a fan 
favorite for his talent and character, while we expect Green to be 
a solid player for us next season. There's also no doubt Biron and 
the eighth overall will emerge as important contributors to this 
franchise for years to come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The trade was made after failed attempts to send Palffy and  
defenseman Rich Pilon to the New York Rangers for a package that 
included forwards Todd Harvey and Niklas Sundstrom. Islanders 
ownership effectively killed the deal by making extra financial 
demands of the Rangers after the league approved a $2.5 million 
cash exchange. That prompted NHL commissioner Gary Bettman to 
disallow any trade of Palffy that included cash. The league also 
monitored the trade to make sure the Islanders were getting at 
least one bona-fide NHL player in the deal. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
