<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Air System Pilots End Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Pilots at Japan's third largest airline ended their  
strike early Sunday after management agreed to withdraw plans to 
train pilots at a subsidiary, the airline said. 
</P>
<P>
	With the agreement, operations at Japan Air System Co. returned  
to normal and no flights were canceled Sunday, said company 
spokesman Jun Miyazaki. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline had been forced to cancel 21 flights on Friday and  
another 28 on Saturday because of the walkout, Miyazaki said. 
</P>
<P>
	All the canceled flights were on domestic routes and a total of  
8,700 passengers were affected, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The strike began in April, when the airline's 712 pilots and  
copilots walked out to protest a management proposal to contract 
out some operation to a subsidiary as a cost-cutting measure. 
</P>
<P>
	But the airline had avoided cancellations by staffing flights  
with management-class pilots, who are not allowed to join unions 
under Japanese labor laws. 
</P>
<P>
	With an expansion of the strike on Friday, however,  
cancellations became unavoidable, the airline said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 12:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Examine Animal-Hoarders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- They're dismissed as wacky animal-loving  
eccentrics, those people discovered with dozens, even hundreds, of 
pets living under one roof. 
</P>
<P>
	Animal experts have a name for them -- hoarders. But their  
behavior may not always be simply idiosyncratic, researchers say. 
It could signal mental illness. 
</P>
<P>
	The cases crop up with alarming frequency, and make for splashy  
headlines. There's the woman in Sugar Land, Texas, with 74 cats and 
dogs, a dozen of which died in a March fire; the couple in Methuen 
with as many as 150 cats discovered after a July blaze; the 
Northampton woman found last fall with 100 felines. 
</P>
<P>
	A team of Massachusetts veterinarians and psychologists is  
trying now to figure out why love for pets sometimes turns into 
animal obsession. 
</P>
<P>
	``Historically, their behavior was excused. People would say,  
`They just love animals, why not leave them alone?''' said Gary 
Patronek, director of the Center for Animals and Public Policy at 
Tufts University School of Veterinary Medicine in Grafton. 
</P>
<P>
	Recently, that attitude has been shifting as closer attention is  
paid to the deplorable state in which such animals often live. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoarded pets are typically worm-ridden, underfed, mangy and  
stressed out. They live -- and frequently die -- in squalor. 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the worst cases are discovered after neighbors complain  
of a foul stench. That's when animal control officers or health 
inspectors find dead cats piled under couches and foot-deep 
excrement on the floor. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoarders can be prosecuted under animal cruelty laws. But  
convictions are more likely to lead to small fines than prison 
time. Many hoarders start all over again after they are caught. 
</P>
<P>
	There is no way to track exactly how many occur, although  
Patronek estimates at least 2,000 are discovered annually. 
</P>
<P>
	This year he set up a national surveillance effort to try to  
pinpoint the problem and also hopes to interview the hoarders to 
determine their motives. 
</P>
<P>
	In research published in January, Patronek studied 54 such cases  
from around the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The median number of animals kept was 39, but some hoarded as  
many as 100. 
</P>
<P>
	The keepers often viewed themselves as saviors on a rescue  
mission. Of the cases studied, 76 percent involved women, and 46 
percent were over age 69. Abut half lived alone. 
</P>
<P>
	In 80 percent of the cases, animals were found dead,  
malnourished or injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Cats tend to be hoarded most often, since they are relatively  
small, quiet and easy to hide. But even farm animals have been 
kept. 
</P>
<P>
	With the high recidivism rate, Patronek said, prosecution will  
do little to curb the behavior. With help from behavioral 
psychologists and sociologists at Smith College, Boston University 
and Northeastern University, Patronek is examining whether animal 
hoarders would be better helped by mental health experts. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are forced to prosecute these folks because there  
aren't alternatives,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 11:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Norsk Owns 90 Pct. of Petroleum Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OSLO, Norway (AP) -- The Norsk Hydro ASA concern Sunday announced  
that it now controls more than 90 percent of Saga Petroleum ASA's 
shares, apparently winning a bidding war with France's Elf 
Aquitaine. 
</P>
<P>
	The 51-percent state-owned Norsk Hydro and the Norwegian state  
oil company Statoil ASA jointly bid $17.30 per share in stocks and 
cash for Saga Petroleum. Acceptances had to be postmarked by 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In a news release Sunday, Norsk Hydro said a preliminary count  
showed that well over 70 percent of Saga's shareholders had 
accepted the offer by that deadline. In addition, Statoil already 
held 19.4 percent of the shares. 
</P>
<P>
	``This means the two companies, combined, will control more than  
90 percent of Saga's shares,'' the news release said. Norsk Hydro, 
an oil, fertilizers and light metals concern which is the largest 
company on the Oslo Stock Exchange, said a final figure is expected 
on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal is contingent on endorsement from Norsk Hydro's  
shareholders at a meeting on Wednesday, and on approval by 
regulatory agencies in Norway and the European Union. 
</P>
<P>
	A bid by Elf, which made a cash-only offer of $16.02 per share  
for Norway's third-largest oil company, expires on Friday, June 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Norsk Hydro and Statoil have agreed to split Saga's assets so  
that Norsk Hydro gets 75 percent and the state oil company takes 
the rest. Saga's unions opposed the deal, because it would mean 
closing their company. The government favored the offer, because it 
would keep Saga's resources in Norwegian hands. 
</P>
<P>
	Saga Petroleum has reserves of roughly 1.5 billion barrels of  
oil equivalents, but had announced tough austerity measures after 
reporting losses for 1998. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 15:26:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Stephen King Alert After Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEWISTON, Maine (AP) -- Stephen King was alert and in good  
spirits Sunday after surgery for injuries suffered when he was 
struck by a van while walking along a rural Maine highway. 
</P>
<P>
	The prolific best-selling horror author remained in serious but  
stable condition, and faces additional surgery this week, said 
Chuck Gill, a spokesman for Central Maine Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said King was thrown 14 feet when he was hit Saturday  
by a Dodge Caravan in rural Lovell, where he owns a summer home. 
</P>
<P>
	Chip Baker, who witnessed the accident, told WCSH-TV in Portland  
that he rushed to help King. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was bleeding and he was laying in a heap and all tangled  
up,'' Baker said. ``It just happened so quick, you know. I knew he 
was in kind of rough shape in either his leg or his hip.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gill said King suffered a collapsed lung and multiple fractures  
of the right leg and hip. He was also treated during surgery at 
around 3:30 a.m. for a scalp laceration. 
</P>
<P>
	King was conscious and alert after he emerged from the  
operation. His wife, Tabitha, his children and other relatives were 
by King's side. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's been alert and he's in pretty good spirits,'' Gill said.  
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Sunday, hospital spokesman Laird Covey said King had  
been talking with his wife, adding, ``I know that he has been 
cracking some jokes to the staff about his condition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	King was walking south on the shoulder of state Route 5 at about  
4:30 p.m. Saturday when a motorist approaching from behind lost 
control of his vehicle because of a dog that was loose inside, 
Oxford County Sheriff's deputy Matt Baker said. 
</P>
<P>
	According to witnesses, the driver, Bryan Smith, 41, did not  
appear to be speeding, Baker said. He said no charges will be filed 
against Smith. 
</P>
<P>
	King, who lives in Bangor, may have been on one of his daily  
long walks at his summer home when he was struck, Covey said. 
Lovell is about 115 miles southwest of Bangor. 
</P>
<P>
	King has written more than two dozen novels, including ``The  
Shining,'' ``Carrie'' and ``Pet Sematary.'' King's ``The Girl Who 
Loved Tom Gordon'' is on several best seller lists this weekend. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 15:26:00 </DATE_TIME>
