<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 00:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres Lose Cup But Gain Respect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- The Buffalo Sabres had hoped to make  
history in the Stanley Cup finals. Instead, they ended up repeating 
it after a disputed goal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres saw their bid for a Stanley Cup snatched by the  
Dallas Stars, who made some history of their own with a 2-1 
triple-overtime win in Game 6 on Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Brett Hull scored the winner 14:51 into the third overtime of  
the second longest game ever in the Cup finals. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres disputed the goal, saying Hull violated the league's  
in-the-crease rule. The league said the goal would stand. 
</P>
<P>
	``His foot was in the crease when he scored the goal,'' Sabres  
coach Lindy Ruff said. ``You can't explain that to me. That was the 
worst nightmare right there. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have 200 people on the ice,'' Ruff said referring to the  
on-ice celebration that began shortly after Hull scored. ``They're 
not going to review it. I just wanted an explanation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even in street clothes, Buffalo still clung to the faint hope  
that its misfortune would be reversed by a ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't wait to see what's going to be done about it,'' Sabres  
forward Joe Juneau said. ``It was a gutless move.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sabres goaltender Dominik Hasek said he didn't realize the  
controversial nature of the goal until he looked at the replay; 
then he wanted to put his jersey back on and return to the ice. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still cannot believe it,'' he said. ``It's really a shame. I  
don't know what the video judge was doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres, looking to end 29 years of frustration for a city  
whose fans needed more misery like they needed another abandoned 
building, replayed the misfortunes of the 1975 Buffalo team. 
</P>
<P>
	That team, fueled by the French Connection line of Rene Robert,  
Gil Perreault and Rick Martin, lost in the finals to the 
Philadelphia Flyers in six games and dropped the deciding game at 
Buffalo's old Aud. 
</P>
<P>
	But this time the Sabres set a new mark for frustration.  
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo's improbable run to the 1999 finals crashed on a night  
when its sputtering offense roared to life with 54 shots but could 
beat Dallas goaltender Ed Belfour only once. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres had a strong start and a powerful finish this season.  
In between, they were mediocre. 
</P>
<P>
	They led the Eastern Conference at the All-Star break but slid  
all the way to No. 7 in the seedings due to a mid-season scoring 
slump and a groin injury sustained by Hasek in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo won three playoff series as the underdog and without  
home ice advantage in each. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek, who led the Czech Republic to Olympic gold in 1998,  
failed to win Stanley Cup silver despite 49 saves Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I expected it to be this hard,'' said Stars center Mike  
Modano, who came under fire from the Sabres before the series for 
suggesting they weren't a worthy opponent in the final. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone thinks they're not a great team,'' Modano said. ``But  
their goals-against was second in the league, so we knew it was 
going to be tough to create chances and opportunities. It's funny 
that everybody said they were underdogs. I didn't think that going 
into it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas got the Cup, but Buffalo earned respect.  
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't know a lot about them coming into the series, but  
any team that makes it to the Stanley Cup final is a good team,'' 
Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk said. ``They were a gritty team and 
they played hard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Sabres are likely to make more noise in future  
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have a young team, they skate well, they play defense  
well and they have a great goalie,'' he said. ``They've got a good 
nucleus of players to build on.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 15:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Umpire Leaves Note for Pitchers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Using his feet, umpire John Shulock told everyone  
at Tiger Stadium exactly how he feels about pitchers who do not 
throw the ball over the plate. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after Detroit's Brian Moehler walked two Oakland batters  
in the second inning Sunday, Shulock scratched a note in the 
infield dirt: ``3-2 Why.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shulock was working at second base. He neatly stepped out his  
message near the edge of the grass, behind the shortstop spot. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't understand why no one throws strikes,'' Shulock said  
after the Athletics' 6-5 victory. ``Everyone wants to go to a full 
count every time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I mean, look at the most successful pitchers, the Greg  
Madduxes and Tom Glavines. They throw strike one, strike two. Now 
they're ahead, and maybe they get a batter to swing at a bad pitch. 
But there's too much of this ball one, ball two.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shulock, known as one of baseball's better balls-and-strikes  
umpires, laughed and smiled while he made his remarks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was just having fun out there,'' said Shulock, a member of  
the AL staff since 1979. ``Just passing time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit shortstop Deivi Cruz took note of Shulock's footwook.  
</P>
<P>
	``He read it, looked over and said, `You're right,' '' Shulock  
recalled. 
</P>
<P>
	The note did not last too long, however. It got erased when  
groundskeepers swept the dirt in the middle innings. 
</P>
<P>
	There were nine walks in the Oakland-Detroit game. While walk  
totals seem to be increasing in the majors, some observers blame 
the umpires for not calling enough strikes. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one wants to be out all night long,'' Shulock said. ``The  
pitchers don't want to be. So throw the ball over the plate and you 
might get them 1-2-3.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Players occasionally use their cleats to scrawl messages in the  
infield dirt. Dick Allen became notorious in Philadelphia for his 
notes, which included ``Boo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Chicago White Sox shortstop Mike Caruso scratched out  
``Hi Deivi'' in a game against the Tigers. Caruso and Cruz had 
played against each other in the minors. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not the first time I've done it,'' Shulock said.  
``Sometimes you just come up with things.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 20:47:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AMA Wrestles With Doctors Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Frustrated by managed care companies, hundreds of  
doctors gathered Sunday at the American Medical Association's 
annual meeting to debate the merits and risks of forming a labor 
union. 
</P>
<P>
	``American physicians are angry, frustrated and exhausted over  
the intrusions of third-party payors into the day-to-day practice 
of medicine,'' said Dr. William G. Gamel, a delegate from Austin, 
Texas, and director of that state's Medicaid program. 
</P>
<P>
	``And they are looking to us, their representatives at the  
local, state, specialty and national levels, to help them find a 
way to practice their profession as they've been trained.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gamel spoke on the opening day of the AMA's annual convention,  
where 494 delegates representing about 290,000 doctors, or about 
one-third of U.S. physicians, began meeting for five days to set 
policy for the influential group. 
</P>
<P>
	At their winter meeting in December, the delegates asked AMA  
trustees to investigate collective bargaining, and the trustees 
responded with a 70-page report that served as a starting point for 
debate about what the AMA can do without violating antitrust laws. 
</P>
<P>
	``The House of Delegates resolution was `to level the playing  
field.' ... There is no vehicle that will do that totally,'' said 
AMA board president Dr. Randolph D. Smoak Jr., in an interview last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether it's a traditional labor union or what we call a union  
without striking, ... you have to have an employer-employee 
relationship under the National Labor Relations Act. Otherwise you 
are subject to huge antitrust problems,'' he said, adding that only 
one of every seven U.S. physicians is an employee under the federal 
law's definition. 
</P>
<P>
	Some doctors who debated Sunday said the AMA must take an  
activist role. 
</P>
<P>
	``More testosterone is needed by the AMA,'' said Dr. Michael  
Connair, an orthopedic surgeon in New Haven, Conn. ``I am not 
asking that the AMA establish how a collective bargaining unit 
should be formed, it doesn't have the expertise or wisdom to do so. 
... But it does have the moral authority to establish the 
guidelines,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are now 25 states with private labor unions for  
physicians, and if the AMA does not involve itself now, with those 
that exist and those that will exist, ... then the AMA will lose 
its credibility,'' Connair said, a union activist. 
</P>
<P>
	Delegates will vote later in the week on whether to adopt a  
specific policy. 
</P>
<P>
	The delegates on Sunday elected Smoak, a surgeon from South  
Carolina, to be their new president-elect. He ran unopposed and 
will take over the largely speech-making position next summer, 
after the term of incoming president Dr. Thomas R. Reardon. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 15:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
