<DOCNO> APW19990620.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 13:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Live in Ark., NY </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLOGNE, Germany (AP) -- President Clinton, turning his attention  
to matters at home, said Sunday that he plans to divide his 
post-presidential time between Arkansas and New York and will work 
hard on issues he cares about -- since he's not good enough at golf 
to become a professional. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Hillary Rodham Clinton, if she becomes ``Senator  
Clinton,'' she would ``obviously have to spend a lot more time,'' 
in New York, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He brushed off speculation Mrs. Clinton is considering moving  
out of the White House and getting a place to live in New York. 
``Not true,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with CNN's ``Late Edition'' following his summit  
meetings with counterparts from the world's richest nations, 
Clinton also gave what amounted to a campaign speech for his wife. 
</P>
<P>
	``She has been the most consistently seriously dedicated to the  
kinds of public issues that I think are important today, to the 
welfare of children, the strength of families, the future of 
education, quality of health care,'' he said. ``If the people of 
New York chose her, they would have somebody with 30 years of 
unbroken, consistent, committed dedication, who knows a lot and is 
great with working with people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He and Mrs. Clinton, shortly after settling in at the White  
House, agreed they would move to New York when his time in office 
ended, Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would divide my time between New York and going home to  
Arkansas, and finishing my library and doing my work there,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If she runs for the Senate, she'll obviously have to spend a  
lot more time there (in New York),'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``But it will be like an incumbent member of Congress running  
for re-election. That is, she's not going to stop being first lady 
and doing her other responsibilities, but she'll have to spend a 
lot more time in New York, and we'll have to get a place there for 
her to be while she's spending the time there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A New York Daily News poll Sunday gave Mrs. Clinton a slight  
lead in a hypothetical Senate race with New York City Mayor Rudolph 
Giuliani. The first lady led the mayor 47 to 39 percent, but the 
poll had a margin of error of plus or minus 4 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll also found that nearly three-fourths of voters do not  
feel it is a conflict for Mrs. Clinton to run for Senate while 
still serving as first lady. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton gave some insight into his plans for after he leaves  
office. He said he would work on issues of world peace and the 
reconciliation of people across racial and religious lines and be 
involved with young people. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to work hard,'' he said, adding that he is too young to  
retire and ``I'm not good enough to go on the senior golf tour.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton ducked an opportunity to evaluate Texas Gov. George W.  
Bush's qualifications to be president. ``That's a decision the 
American people have to make,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush declared his candidacy last week for the Republican  
presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Bush must be more specific about where he stands, the  
president said. 
</P>
<P>
	``His announcement speech was very well crafted and was  
strikingly reminiscent of what those of us who call ourselves new 
Democrats have been saying since 1991,'' Clinton said, ``but on the 
specifics, I just don't know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Turning to Vice President Al Gore, who also announced last week,  
Clinton said he ``took no offense'' if Gore was trying to distance 
himself from Clinton when he deplored Clinton's behavior in his 
affair with former intern Monica Lewinsky. 
</P>
<P>
	``He didn't say anything that I hadn't said in much starker  
terms a long time ago.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
