<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 12:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Victims' Relatives Defend Williams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Emanuel Jones remembers his grandmother sending  
him and his brother Clifford to the grocery store that August day 
20 years ago, the day Clifford was strangled and his body dumped 
behind a Laundromat. 
</P>
<P>
	``She told us don't split up, walk together, hold hands,'' Jones  
said, recalling the fear that gripped Atlanta during 1979-81 when 
police investigated the slayings of 29 young blacks, including 
Clifford. 
</P>
<P>
	At the grocery store, Jones let Clifford stay out front to  
hustle money carrying groceries for customers, while he went inside 
to buy the breakfast food their grandmother wanted. He never saw 
his brother alive again. 
</P>
<P>
	``I blamed it all on myself for years because I let him go,''  
said Jones, now 33. ``I let him do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Partly to assuage his guilt, Jones recently returned to Atlanta  
from Chattanooga, Tenn., to launch his own investigation. For 
weeks, he pored through police files and interviewed witnesses. 
</P>
<P>
	``I found out for one that Wayne Williams didn't kill my  
brother,'' he said. ``There were others involved in the murder .... 
My brother's case has never been solved.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the investigation of Clifford's slaying officially was  
closed in 1982, after Williams was convicted of murder in two of 
the 29 deaths. Authorities blamed Williams for 22 of the other 
slayings, including Clifford's, on the basis of fiber evidence 
taken from the victims' bodies and matched to sources in Williams' 
home and cars. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, some of the victims' families have become defenders  
of the man blamed for killing their children, unsuccessfully asking 
the Justice Department and the city to reopen the case. 
</P>
<P>
	``They didn't want nothing else to do with it after he was  
convicted,'' said Willie Mae Mathis, mother of 11-year-old Jefferey 
Mathis, one of the slayings not officially blamed on Williams. 
``They just pushed it all under the rug.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, some victims' mothers are working with Williams' lawyers,  
trying to enlist the aid of Atlanta's black clergy to persuade the 
new Fulton County new district attorney, Paul Howard, to launch a 
new investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, an appeal filed by Williams is pending before the  
Georgia Supreme Court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 16:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Finals Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Madison Square Garden is as famous for its  
villains as it is for the tradition and rivalries that have played 
out inside the historic arena. 
</P>
<P>
	On the court Sunday during practice for Monday night's Game 3 of  
the NBA Finals, finding a villain wearing a San Antonio Spurs 
uniform was no easy task. 
</P>
<P>
	That is, until Sean Elliott opened his mouth.  
</P>
<P>
	Asked if playing in the Garden means anything to him, Elliott  
said this: 
</P>
<P>
	``At the risk of being burned at the stake, it doesn't. I grew  
up on the West Coast. I think a lot of guys from the East love this 
building and they love to play here. They followed maybe the Knicks 
and Celtics and some of the great rivalries back in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me, I get goose bumps walking into the Forum. That's the  
place for me. I wasn't a Knick fan growing up. I was actually a 
Laker-hater. So to go in and beat the Lakers in the Forum meant a 
lot for me. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know people talk about MSG, but I've always walked in here  
like it was a regular arena.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Jordan electrified the Garden like no other visiting  
player, having some of his best games in the arena off Broadway. 
Reggie Miller hit some huge shots here, and rubbed many of them in 
with shameless trash talk. Every Knicks fan remembers Miller 
clutching his throat after hitting a 3-pointer in front of Spike 
Lee during the 1994 Eastern Conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	So who plays this role for the Spurs? Who dons the black hat,  
talks the trash, spews the invective that ends up in back-page 
headlines? 
</P>
<P>
	Elliott's comments about the Garden aside, he doesn't exactly  
make a great villain. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody knows me by now, I'm not a trash-talker,'' Elliott  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	David Robinson doesn't appear ready to seize the role, either.  
</P>
<P>
	``Madison Square Garden, what better place in the world is there  
to play when you're playing a big game?'' Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mario Elie, a native New Yorker who grew up near the Garden,  
knows the importance of the building. Still, he's not worried about 
putting the Spurs' 6-0 road record in the playoffs on the line. 
</P>
<P>
	``After playing in front of 39,000, I think 19,000 is going to  
be nothing,'' Elie said. ``The toughest part to me is just the 
nasty crowd you guys got here. The crowd is nasty, they're loud, 
they're knowledgeable. I mean, this is just a great, festive 
atmosphere. 
</P>
<P>
	``The music is going to be loud, the dancers are going to be  
hot. Jerry (Seinfeld) and Woody (Allen), everybody is going to be 
fired up. Spike's going to have his towel going. It's going to be a 
great challenge for our guys, and our guys are looking forward to 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *NEW WHAT?:* Spurs point guard Avery Johnson loves the idea of  
coming to New York. He compares it with his native New Orleans 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a city with flare,'' he said. ``There's so much to do.  
Any town with a lot of different restaurants is good. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard for me when I go to Utah.''  
</P>
<P>
	Tim Duncan said, ``I'm not a big city guy. It's a great city, a  
lot of fun. I don't know if I could live here for any extended 
period of time.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *IDLE 7-FOOTER:* San Antonio center Will Perdue hasn't played a  
single minute in Games 1 and 2. If he played for the injury-ravaged 
Knicks, he'd probably be their starter. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know, I've talked about that with friends,'' said Perdue,  
who played sparingly this season as the backup to backup power 
forward Malik Rose. ``I think there'd be a good possibility of it, 
yeah.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perdue was a starter for several games last season when San  
Antonio went with a Triple Towers starting frontline featuring 
himself, David Robinson and Tim Duncan. As for this series, Perdue 
is just hoping to get off the bench to do more than lean against 
the press table and stretch his calves. 
</P>
<P>
	``So far, we've had two games and I haven't had any moments,''  
Perdue said. ``But I have a feeling there will be a time for me to 
do something, and I have to remain ready for whenever that time may 
be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perdue, who will be a free agent this summer, says San Antonio  
and Detroit are the places he'd most like to play next season. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LEAVE ME BE:* New York's Larry Johnson was 2-for-12 in Game 2,  
including 1-for-7 from 3-point range. Addressing a large crowd of 
media on Sunday, Johnson offered this profane assessment of how his 
sprained knee affected his shooting: 
</P>
<P>
	``It didn't bother me because of the pain, it bothered me  
because I couldn't practice,'' he said. ``Just like now. I can't 
get any shots up with y'all ... bothering me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later Sunday, Johnson and the Knicks were each fined $25,000 for  
the obscenities and because Johnson did not make himself available 
for the entire 30-minute mandatory media session. It was the second 
time this postseason Johnson and the team were fined. The league 
fined them $10,000 each on June 8 because Johnson twice failed to 
make himself available to the media following practices on June 4 
and 5. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *WHO NEEDS TICKETS?:* Spurs forward Malik Rose has seven friends  
and family members taking a train from Philadelphia to attend Game 
3. Mario Elie, a native New Yorker, purchased 22 tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's only a couple grand, so I can live with it,'' Elie said.  
``If we win, the bonus money will make up for it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
