<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 11:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Numbers Can Wear an Investor Out / Ticker Talk  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- To see why so many advisers urge a patient,  
long-term approach to investing, look at the up-and-down numbers 
game played out on Wall Street over the past few weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The April report on inflation was worse than expected, and stock  
prices plunged. Then the May consumer price index came in better 
than expected, and stock prices soared. 
</P>
<P>
	Here's a warning: By some analysts' preliminary reckoning, the  
CPI increase for June looks as though it might jump back to a scary 
level. Could the market tumble again? 
</P>
<P>
	From the stock market's day-by-day reactions to each statistical  
announcement that comes along, you get an impression of investors 
in a frantic scramble to keep up as the world spins faster and 
faster. 
</P>
<P>
	But if you take a slightly longer perspective, the zigs and zags  
on the charts lose some of their sharp edges, and the game looks a 
little more rational. Instead of an impossible melee, the market 
presents itself as a reasonable, even though absolutely 
unpredictable, place in which to take calculated risks with your 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	As of late last week, the popular stock averages showed  
year-to-date gains of 5 percent to 20 percent, depending on the 
sector of the market they measure. The Dow Jones industrial average 
stood just slightly above where it was two months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	That's a very good showing -- double-digit gains all around when  
you project them out to annual rates -- in keeping with an economy 
that still is bursting with signs of vitality. 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of June the Federal Reserve may well push short-term  
interest rates higher in an effort to cool down the economy a bit. 
The markets, which always anticipate, seem almost to have worn 
themselves out discounting every possible choice the Fed might 
make, and now stand not far from where they were before the whole 
inflation scare arose. 
</P>
<P>
	It has proved not only futile, but also unnecessary, for  
investors to figure out each twist and turn of the story. 
</P>
<P>
	``How long will the current short-term desire to buy stocks  
last? We have no idea,'' says George Putnam III in his Boston-based 
advisory The Turnaround Letter. ``Given the diversity of the group 
who currently want to buy stocks, it is virtually impossible to 
predict what will make them change their minds and when it will 
happen. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fortunately for our reputation, we didn't advise anyone to get  
out of stocks two years ago when the Asian crisis broke or last 
summer when Russia's economy imploded. And we are not going to do 
so now, even though we are quite concerned about rising interest 
rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``Successfully anticipating stock-market movements requires not  
only that you correctly forecast world economic trends and events, 
but also that you predict the reactions of a large and diverse 
group of human beings. We certainly can't do both of those, and we 
don't know anyone who can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Once you decide not to try to outguess the economic data or the  
markets, the question naturally arises what you are going to do to 
protect yourself from long bear markets and other calamities. 
</P>
<P>
	The time-honored answer is to diversify, keeping your money  
spread out to minimize the potential damage from disaster in any 
one stock, mutual fund, or market for that matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Now is a great time, for instance, to have some money in the  
stock market, and some money NOT in the stock market. Also, to keep 
money that is earmarked for interest-bearing securities diversified 
between long-term bonds and the short-term money markets. 
</P>
<P>
	That way your overall portfolio won't be knocked off balance  
whether the Fed tightens credit conditions or not. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 17:50:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CART Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Helio Castro-Neves knows how to grab the  
lead. Holding onto it, and staying in the race altogether, is 
proving more difficult for the 24-year-old Brazilian. 
</P>
<P>
	Castro-Neves led the first 30 laps of the Budweiser-G.I. Joe's  
200 on Sunday before dropping out because of a blown turbocharger. 
It was the second straight time, and fourth in eight races this 
season, that the second-year CART FedEx Series driver led at least 
part of the way and failed to finish. 
</P>
<P>
	In the season-opener in Homestead, Fla., he finished 17th  
dropping out because of electrical problems. In Nazareth, Pa., he 
started second but finished 21st after a crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks ago in Milwaukee, Castro-Neves won the pole position  
and had the fastest car early on, but ended up retiring because of 
a turbocharger problem, finishing 26th. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, he appeared in command on Portland International  
Raceway's narrow nine-turn course. After pitting just before the 
31st lap, he was second to Juan Montoya, and the pair were pulling 
away from the pack when Castro-Neves gradually began losing power. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was bad luck,'' he said. ``I was handling it, I was  
saving fuel because I know this race is kind of fuel strategy. The 
car was handling well. What can I say?'' 
</P>
<P>
	After falling into fourth, 16.4 seconds behind Montoya,  
Castro-Neves retired on the 39th lap. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BAD YEAR ENDS: It was a good day for Goodyear, whose tires held  
out just long enough to carry Gil de Ferran to victory. 
</P>
<P>
	De Farran's win broke a 25-race losing streak by Goodyear dating  
to the 1998 season opener in Homestead. After Michael Andretti won 
that race, drivers rode Firestones to victory in the last 18 races 
of 1998, and the first seven this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Goodyear and I haven't won a race for a couple of years, but  
it was only a matter of time,'' de Ferran said. 
</P>
<P>
	de Ferran tested Goodyears twice on the PIR course, and team  
owner Derrick Walker had confidence on the tires late in the race. 
Running low on fuel and leading by about 29 seconds, the crew took 
just 5.4 seconds to splash some fuel in. The tires stayed on for 
the last 39 laps. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were perfect,'' de Ferran said. ``They had a lot of grip,  
and they were consistent throughout the final run. If they weren't 
consistent, I would never have been able to open up that gap.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	COSTLY DELAY: Despite a stall that cost him more than a minute,  
Michael Andretti fought back for a 10th-place finish, 58.7 seconds 
behind winner Gil de Ferran. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the engine shut down after my first stop, our race was  
pretty much dictated then,'' said Andretti, who picked up five 
points in the PPG Cup standings but dropped from fourth to sixth 
with 64 points. 
</P>
<P>
	On a day in which the main question was whether to pit two or  
three times, Andretti played the fuel conservation game well. On 
the 34th lap, Andretti was the last to pit, and was getting ready 
to challenge the leaders when his wheels spun after refueling. The 
engine stalled, and his crew had to pull the car back to restart 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	When Andretti left pit road, he was next-to-last in 25th place  
before climbing back. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's so disappointing, because it is out of our control,'' he  
said. ``Every other aspect of the race went smoothly. We did 
perfect pit stops and were able to conserve fuel.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	PIT STOPS: Memo Gidley and Gualter Salles made their 1999 CART  
debuts Sunday, and rookie Gidley fared better. Gidley, de Ferran's 
Walker Racing teammate, started 25th in the 28-car field and 
finished 19th. Salles, who recently replaced rookie Alex Barron for 
Dan Gurney's All-American Racing team, had gearbox problems and 
quit after just 10 laps, finishing ahead of only Shigeaki Hattori 
of Japan. ... Following two injuries to pit crew members in the 
last two races, CART officials followed the lead of the crews and 
wore helmets in the pit for the first time. ... Arciero-Wells 
Racing announced it signed rookie driver Cristiano da Matta of 
Brazil through the year 2000. Da Matta finished 11th and stands 
17th in the season points. ... de Ferran finished second twice in 
Portland, including 1996 and 1997, when he lost to Mark Blundell by 
0.027-seconds, the closest finish in CART history. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 20:52:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Braves Manager Ejected From Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Atlanta manager Bobby Cox was thrown out of  
Sunday night's game against the Arizona Diamondbacks in the first 
inning, his fifth ejection of the season and second in five days. 
</P>
<P>
	Plate umpire Jeff Kellogg tossed Cox with one out and the bases  
loaded. 
</P>
<P>
	Cox never left the dugout before he was ejected, but he was  
letting Kellogg know what he thought of the strike zone after 
Atlanta's Tom Glavine walked two of his first four batters. 
</P>
<P>
	Kellogg walked to the dugout and warned Cox after Arizona's Matt  
Williams walked on a 3-2 pitch that loaded the bases. As Steve 
Finley prepared to bat, Kellogg turned to the dugout again, pointed 
at Cox and ordered him out of the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Cox rushed from the dugout to argue with Kellogg to the cheers  
of the big crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second time this season Cox was tossed in the first  
inning. It also happened May 11 in San Francisco. He also was 
tossed Wednesday at Houston. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990620.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 20:52:37 </DATE_TIME>
