<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 17:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Awaits End to Economic Woes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- What do you do with an economy when even free money  
fails to generate much excitement? 
</P>
<P>
	That's the dilemma Japan faces.  
</P>
<P>
	Interest rates are so low loans cost next to nothing, yet  
businesses aren't borrowing. The government has handed out billions 
of dollars in free shopping vouchers, but nervous consumers aren't 
spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``People just put their money in the bank in case the economy  
gets worse,'' said Hanako Hara, a woman selling tickets for the 
national lottery at a downtown booth. ``They're even buying fewer 
lottery tickets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the anniversary of the financial crisis that struck Asia in  
the summer of 1997, there are signs the worst may be over for 
hard-hit countries like South Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	But a decade after Japan's ``bubble economy'' of the 1980s began  
to deflate, Japanese leaders are still wondering how to fix it. 
</P>
<P>
	After stumbling along at an average growth rate of just over 1  
percent a year between 1992 and 1997, Japan's economy sank into its 
longest postwar recession, shrinking for more than a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The economy finally grew again in the first quarter of this  
year, expanding a robust 1.9 percent, the government reported June 
10. 
</P>
<P>
	But serious problems remain, analysts warn.  
</P>
<P>
	``At best this is a stabilization, not a recovery,'' said Andrew  
Ballingal, an economist for Schroders Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	During the 1980s, clever bureaucrats were credited with  
engineering an economic miracle by focusing resources on strategic 
industries. ``Japan Inc.'' seemed unstoppable, and people were 
confident the good times would never end. 
</P>
<P>
	In the summer of 1989, the benchmark Nikkei 225 stock average  
was soaring toward the 40,000 mark, doubling in just three years. 
Investors seemed to believe it would never stop. 
</P>
<P>
	But as prices spiraled higher, finance officials realized Japan  
was trapped in a speculative bubble. They moved to rein it in by 
tightening credit. 
</P>
<P>
	The brakes grabbed too hard. The Nikkei tumbled 39 percent in  
1990 after peaking at 38,916 at the end of 1989. Land prices sank 
by half or more over the next several years. 
</P>
<P>
	The collapse did damage to corporate balance sheets that lingers  
still, said Richard Koo, an economist at Nomura Research Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	``People said: `It's temporary. In a few years it will go back  
up again.' But once they realized that wasn't going to happen they 
got pretty scared,'' Koo said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials have tried a series of measures to ease those fears.  
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan slashed its discount rate -- the rate at which  
it lends to banks -- from 6 percent at the beginning of the decade 
to 0.5 percent in 1995. Then, this March, it pushed a key 
short-term interest rate to zero. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, companies saddled with excess equipment and facilities  
have little need to borrow, and banks are too preoccupied with 
cleaning up bad loans to make new ones. Worries about job losses 
have made consumers reluctant to spend more. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Japan's jobless rate among men jumped to an all-time  
high of 5 percent, while overall unemployment remained at a record 
4.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has earmarked more than $500 billion in this  
year's budget for tax cuts, spending on roads and bridges and other 
measures intended to stimulate the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The growth spurt in the first quarter was built almost entirely  
on those outlays. 
</P>
<P>
	But economists worry the growth report could make policy makers  
complacent and prompt them to back off on government spending 
before private investment and consumption are strong enough to 
drive growth. 
</P>
<P>
	That has happened before. The economy picked up nicely in 1996,  
but the recovery fizzled after an overly optimistic government 
raised the sales tax in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Other observers worry Japanese leaders aren't addressing the  
economy's worst problems, including the need to simplify 
regulations and create an environment kinder to startup companies. 
</P>
<P>
	A new study even suggests that policies to protect developing  
industries -- the same policies credited for much of Japan Inc.'s 
early success -- have done more harm than good. 
</P>
<P>
	The most competitive industries, such as the video game business  
dominated by Nintendo Co. and Sony Corp., are the ones bureaucrats 
left alone. 
</P>
<P>
	``The single most important lesson for Japan is: Don't mistrust  
competition. Competition is good,'' said Hirotaka Takeuchi, dean of 
Hitotsubashi University's Graduate School of International Strategy 
and one of the study's authors. 
</P>
<P>
	Fixing Japan's problems is crucial. Its economy is bigger than  
all the rest of Asia put together, and economists say the region 
cannot fully recover until Japan is healthy. 
</P>
<P>
	Unless Japan's leaders do something soon, the economy faces ``a  
new negative phase,'' said Ballingal, the Schroders Securities 
economist. 
</P>
<P>
	And, he added, ``What's true for Japan is going to be true for  
all of Asia.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
