<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 22:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> An American Portrait of Columnist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- His mom cried when she found out. His  
dad, he was just a little embarrassed. Their only son, the aspiring 
journalist, had started his newspaper's ... body-piercing beat? 
</P>
<P>
	The Daily Collegian, Penn State's student daily, put it in  
loftier terms: ``Every week, James Conroy gets part of his body 
pierced and records the experience for posterity and the good of 
mankind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Conroy, 21, started with his tongue and proceeded to his ear  
(twice), his chin, his nose, his navel, his nipple -- and yes, even 
that place, as he called it, ``down south.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It had to be done,'' Conroy insists.  
</P>
<P>
	Along the way, he gathered some attention on campus: quotes in  
The Chronicle of Higher Education, photos with female fans at a 
party, an appearance on the Internet wearing only a ``censored'' 
box. 
</P>
<P>
	Plus dozens of e-mails each day from readers suggesting which  
body part to pierce next. Some wanted him to go for the back of his 
neck. Others targeted the webbing between thumb and index finger. 
And, of course... 
</P>
<P>
	``As the saying goes, `Never say never,''' Conroy wrote in his  
column, ``James' Adventures in ... Piercing,'' after waffling for 
weeks about whether to go below the belt. ``If I hadn't done it,'' 
he says now, ``there would have been 40,000 people, theoretically, 
berating me for being a wimp.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Conroy, of Aston, Pa., claims to be normal, citing as evidence  
his conservative taste in fashion and his education at an all-boys' 
Catholic high school. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't come across as an outlandish guy,'' Conroy says. ``If  
you saw me now, you wouldn't even be able to see any of the 
piercings. Once I know people, they see I'm pretty nutty, but I 
don't come across that way to random people on the street.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he had pierced his tongue and eyebrow before, so his editor,  
Jason Fagone, labeled him adventurous. 
</P>
<P>
	The real adventure didn't start until the column's third week,  
when Conroy went for the relatively exotic skin between bottom lip 
and chin. ``The weather was crisp and there was that 
get-a-big-needle-shoved-through-your-lip feeling in the air,'' he 
wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	After the needle came out and the hardware screwed in, Conroy  
started to feel funky. The piercer's voice had changed. ``He was 
sounding like Charlie Brown's teacher: `Wha wha-wha-wha wha wha,''' 
he wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	After drinking loads of Gatorade, Conroy sat down to write and  
doled out one bit of advice: Eat before the pain rushes in. Then he 
developed the Conroy Scale, a pain-o-meter recording 1-to-10. 
</P>
<P>
	The worst of the nine piercings? The nipple.  
</P>
<P>
	The easiest? The tongue. (No nerves down the middle of the  
tongue, he reports.) 
</P>
<P>
	The bloodiest? A barbell at the top of his ear that requires two  
holes. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest problem? The folks who pay his tuition.  
</P>
<P>
	His parents called one Thursday to say they planned to drive in  
-- that weekend. First he spent two hours trying to extricate 
himself from his newest piercing. Then he flipped out, rushed back 
to the piercer and begged him to pull out the chin stud. He did, 
but Conroy still couldn't remove the eyebrow hoop. 
</P>
<P>
	Mom, still in the family's Mercury Sable: ``Take that out.''  
</P>
<P>
	Conroy: ``I've been trying all morning.''  
</P>
<P>
	She wasn't the only person upset. One girl growled at him. One  
reader hoped the next hole in Conroy's body would be ``a .357 
projectile piercing James' temple.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people in the piercing scene hate his guts,'' reports  
Michael Dameron, owner of Forbidden Fruit and the man responsible 
for most of Conroy's holes. ``He reduced it to an MTV-generation 
fad. It really goes a lot deeper than that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Conroy has his fans. One girl asked him out in an e-mail.  
(He passed.) When he contemplated stopping in March, several 
e-mailers urged him to keep going. That kind of response helped him 
through the rough times. ``It's painful,'' he admits. ``It really 
is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some piercings have already disappeared. One fell out, and he  
took out a couple that annoyed him. Two others were victims of his 
summer sojourn home, where neither his mother nor his construction 
job would tolerate the metal baubles. Only three remain -- all of 
them out of sight, usually. 
</P>
<P>
	For pain and suffering, Conroy won a statewide award for best  
collegiate column and may win a journalism scholarship. And his 
hopes for next school year are high: perhaps another stint as a 
columnist or music writer. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper fared well, too. By semester's end, more students  
seemed to be reading the Arts section, and editor Fagone called 
Conroy's column the section's best journalism. 
</P>
<P>
	Forget the question of taste, says Fagone. ``It's fun to get a  
reaction.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
