<DOCNO> APW19990620.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 09:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pawnshop Target of Fed Gun Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UPPER DARBY, Pa. (AP) -- Three, maybe four times each month, one  
suburban pawnshop on the rough edge of Philadelphia takes a phone 
call asking it to trace a gun. 
</P>
<P>
	The caller -- the federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms  
-- won't say whether the weapon has been stolen, abandoned, or 
worse. Just as the ATF won't say now whether Lou's Loan, a bustling 
little shop, is among the tiny percentage of the nation's gun 
dealers recently cited as the source of a large percentage of 
weapons linked to criminal activity. 
</P>
<P>
	The report, released June 7 by Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y.,  
blames 1 percent of the more than 100,000 federally licensed gun 
dealers for nearly half of the crime guns the ATF traced last year. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1996 through 1998, some 34,000 guns used in crimes were  
traced to just over one-tenth of 1 percent of those dealers. The 
report calls these 137 dealers ``bad apples'' and notes that 23 
have already lost their licenses or otherwise quit the business. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the ATF provided statistics on traces for the report, the  
agency doesn't name names of specific dealers, only of the 
communities, such as Upper Darby, where they operate. 
</P>
<P>
	But in the town of 83,000 people, and only a handful of gun  
dealers, Upper Darby police say it must be Lou's. ``A lot of 
weapons have been sold out of Lou's,'' says Detective Sgt. George 
Rhoades. 
</P>
<P>
	Lou's owner, Stanton Myerson, is also sure that his store is on  
Schumer's list. After all, he boasts, his shop sells a lot of guns. 
And, though Myerson refuses to disclose how many, he objects that 
the report fails to take sales volume into account. 
</P>
<P>
	Only a fraction of his firearms fall into criminal hands,  
Myerson insists. And typically, crime guns are stolen from a 
customer or are part of an illegal ``straw purchase,'' in which the 
buyer secretly plans to give the gun away. As Myerson points out, 
if someone is intent on doing harm, ``there's always a way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	From all appearances and by all accounts, Lou's avoids the  
pawnshop stereotype of seamy retailing. Its displays are spotless; 
signs declare the need for a records check. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities give Lou's high marks for obeying state and federal  
gun laws. ``If Lou's was doing anything illegal, they'd be shut 
down,'' says Upper Darby police Capt. Rudy D'Alesio, ``and if the 
ATF didn't do it, we would.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Often the staff at Lou's assist police. With Dennis Wilson's  
help, Duan Seay is heading for old age in prison. Once a regular at 
Lou's, Seay was always browsing, never buying. But his girlfriend 
bought a TEC DC-9, a semiautomatic assault pistol. It jammed and, 
though she returned it for repairs, it was Seay who kept pestering: 
Was it fixed yet? 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson, Lou's best gun dealer, remembered all this one morning  
in 1997 when a broadcast described a holdup that turned into a 
high-speed chase. Two gunmen traded shots with a police officer and 
a stray bullet struck an 8-year-old boy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I happened to see this guy's face on the TV,'' Wilson recalls.  
He pored through records, got the girlfriend's address and called 
the police who arrested Seay. Last year, Seay was sentenced to a 
minimum of 26 1/2 years in prison on robbery, weapons and conspiracy 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The Philadelphia Inquirer last year reported that the ATF traced  
111 crime guns to Lou's between January 1995 and December 1997, an 
average of more than three a month. The ATF will not confirm 
crime-gun traces to Lou's, or any other dealer. Jeffrey Roehm, at 
ATF headquarters in Washington, calls that information ``strictly 
raw data'' -- and no evidence of criminal activity. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency pursues such evidence anywhere it can. An ATF poster  
urges riders taking the 15-minute trip from Philadelphia to Upper 
Darby to report illegal weapons. ``Call 800-ATF-GUNS,'' the 
black-and-white ad pleads. ``We are making a federal case out of 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pitch seems aimed at city dwellers, not residents of Upper  
Darby. Once past the grittiness of its shopping district, the 
community looks largely middle-class and prosperous. Tidy apartment 
complexes and sturdy houses of brick and stone line streets shaded 
by trees. 
</P>
<P>
	Lou's is a few steps from the train station. The shop is one of  
five operating in Pennsylvania and Delaware. The owner's father, 
Louis, founded the first in 1921. 
</P>
<P>
	Tucked under a yellow awning and between a wig shop and a  
jeweler, Lou's storefront displays audio headsets and household 
wares. Signs advertise money orders and check cashing, not guns. 
Myerson says he relies on word of mouth, and ads in the Yellow 
Pages. 
</P>
<P>
	Inside, customers find floor-to-ceiling enticements: a cash  
machine and conga drums, guitars and violins, microwave ovens and 
used power tools. Objects in hock are downstairs, out of sight. 
</P>
<P>
	Most days, Wilson says, buyers stand three deep and five across.  
They come mainly for the guns -- in all, about 125 long guns and 250 
handguns. 
</P>
<P>
	Against a wall, near the back, are racks of rifles priced from  
$300 to $1,200. Most are for hunting, but Lou's also sells 
military-style weapons such as the Colt AR-15 assault rifles that 
buyers like as investments. 
</P>
<P>
	Handguns fill three long glass cases. Propped on green and red  
felt, they cost from $180 to $750. A snapshot of Charlton Heston, 
president of the National Rifle Association, hovers above. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson, like his boss, is a member, and he echoes the group's  
stance on control. ``This gun won't do anything unless this,'' 
Wilson says, pointing to his head, ``makes it do something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet when he learns that a weapon that crossed his counter  
surfaces in a crime, he says: ``We shouldn't be surprised, but I 
always am.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson does what he can to prevent such surprises. He advises  
customers to practice at a firing range, and he instructs them 
on-the-spot in handling and safety. 
</P>
<P>
	He also follows gut instincts. ``I can stop any one I choose,''  
he says. ``If I suspect them in any way, I will deny them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If they appear drugged? Or drunk? Tipsy or irate? ``I won't  
sell.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Come back when you're feeling better,'' he tells them. And, if  
they do come back, still no sale. 
</P>
<P>
	State and federal law allows anyone over 18 without a felony  
record to buy a rifle, but Wilson, the father of a teen-age boy, 
enforces ``our policy.'' Even 18-year-olds aren't allowed to shop 
at Lou's on school days. 
</P>
<P>
	Pennsylvania puts no limit on the number of guns purchased at  
one time, but Wilson restricts sales to two. And anyone who wants 
two gets stern talk. ``If they're not for you,'' he warns, ``you 
will go to jail.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, efforts fail.  
</P>
<P>
	Store manager Charlene Powery tells of a customer in his 70s who  
wanted a downstairs gun for protection, as backup for the one he 
already kept upstairs. After a records check, she sold him a 
handgun. 
</P>
<P>
	Not long after, a woman stormed in, yelling ``murderer!'' and  
waving paperwork on a gun from Lou's. The buyer had delivered the 
gun to a friend dying of cancer, and he used it to kill himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could not sleep for almost a week,'' Ms. Powery recalls.  
``Did you miss something? Did you pay attention? You go over the 
steps, but all your steps are legal.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
