<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Wins World Cricket Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Australia won cricket's World Cup for the second  
time Sunday with an emphatic victory over Pakistan at Lord's. 
</P>
<P>
	The winning margin of eight wickets was a World Cup finals  
record, one more than Sri Lanka had in 1996 against Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Australia, led by captain Steve Waugh, captured its first World  
Cup in 1987. Waugh and Tom Moody are the only remaining members of 
that championship team. 
</P>
<P>
	``Earlier in the tournament we were not doing ourselves  
justice,'' said Waugh, who is 34 and probably played his last World 
Cup. ``I knew we had a good enough side, a side good as any in the 
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	``We scrambled out way through. We had a bit of luck on the way.  
For me this is the best win of my career.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Australians proved resilient throughout the 42-game  
tournament. They fought their way back from the brink of 
elimination when it lost to Pakistan by 10 runs at Headingley on 
May 23. This time, Pakistan appeared tense and overmatched. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were beaten by a better side,'' Pakistan's Wasim Akram  
said. ``They showed their class today. They showed they are the 
best side in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not disappointed in any way. We qualified for the final  
with a very young side. We've got a very bright future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shane Warne, who bowled Australia to a tie in the semifinal  
against South Africa, starred again. His efforts put him on par 
with New Zealand's Geoff Allott as the leading wicket taker with 20 
apiece. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was tough all the way,'' Waugh said. ``I thought the  
defining moment for us was the semifinal, but you've still got to 
make it happen on the day.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
