<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NASCAR Winston Cup Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONG POND, Pa. (AP) -- Two was an unlucky number for Jeff Burton  
at the Pocono 500 on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's my fault,'' Burton said of a second-lap crash that  
relegated him to a 36th-place finish. ``It's not the guy in front's 
fault, it's the guy in back's fault.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Burton collided with Wally Dallenbach after the cars exited the  
sharp tunnel turn at Pocono International Raceway. The crash cost 
him second place in the Winston Cup points race. 
</P>
<P>
	He fell behind race winner Bobby Labonte, and now trails leader  
Dale Jarrett by 186 points after 15 of 34 races. 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte moved within 89 points of Jarrett.  
</P>
<P>
	Burton, whose three victories this year tie him with defending  
series champion Jeff Gordon, apologized for his mistake. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just wasn't anticipating him to get out of the gas and I ran  
into him,'' Burton said of Dallenbach, Gordon's teammate. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SPENCER'S DAY:* Mr. Excitement nearly lived up to his nickname.  
</P>
<P>
	Jimmy Spencer, from nearby Berwick, Pa., was strong late in the  
race as he tried to win for the first time in nearly five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Spencer, who led 14 laps, was especially impressive because he  
made up a lap lost earlier in the race because of a loose lug nut. 
He finished 14th. 
</P>
<P>
	``I realized I had some of the best drivers in the world to  
beat, and they were right behind me,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Spencer's undoing came when he hit some oil while trying to hold  
off Jeff Gordon, Mark Martin, Dale Jarrett and eventual winner 
Bobby Labonte. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I had a chance,'' Spencer said.  
</P>
<P>
	The run was one of the most impressive since he won in 1994 in  
Talladega, Ala. 
</P>
<P>
	Spencer reportedly is seeking another ride next year. His  
sponsor, Winston, has announced it will not return to back the 
effort of car owner Travis Carter. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *WALLACE'S HOOD:* The new hood restraint NASCAR is trying out on  
selected cars got an early test Sunday when Rusty Wallace's car 
slammed into the wall on lap 7. The device seemed to work. 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace's Ford blew its right front tire before going into the  
wall on the first turn, smashing the right side of the car. 
</P>
<P>
	Wallace was not hurt, but called it ``one of the hardest hits  
I've ever had in my life.'' He left the race after the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	The hood, tethered to the chassis by a support cable, didn't  
appear to move or be damaged. Also using the cable were Jeff Gordon 
and race winner Bobby Labonte. 
</P>
<P>
	NASCAR officials speeded up testing of the restraints after a  
May 1 wreck during an Indy Racing League event at Lowe's Motor 
Speedway in Concord, N.C. Three spectators were killed and another 
eight hurt when a wheel and other debris from an accident flew into 
the grandstands. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is basically for fan safety, if these things happen to  
get off the car,'' said Wallace's crew chief, Robin Pemberton. ``It 
shouldn't be a big hassle, not for what you get out of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MARCIS INJURED:* Dave Marcis was taken to a hospital after  
spinning out in turn 2 and hitting the wall. His helmet hit the 
driver's side netting just as the left side of car smashed into the 
wall. 
</P>
<P>
	Marcis sustained a laceration to his chin, and bruises to his  
neck, chest and right ankle. He was taken to Penn State-Geisinger 
Wyoming Valley Hospital for observation and released. 
</P>
<P>
	``He took a hell of a hit, and he's just shaken up by the whole  
thing,'' said business manager Dwayne Leik. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *RUNNING FOR COVER:* Chad Little was penalized four laps after  
skidding while entering pit row and spinning into the wall in front 
of Brett Bodine's pit crew. Nobody was hurt because they scrambled 
to cover in a hurry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
