<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Knicks' Ward Scrambles for Answers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Charlie Ward has the eyes of a scrambler,  
darting this way and that as he exhales, scowls and answers 
questions about his team's plight in the NBA Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Elusiveness was his greatest tool when he was the best high  
school football player in Georgia, and when he won the Heisman 
Trophy at Florida State. 
</P>
<P>
	He is scrambling again, searching for a way to help the New York  
Knicks climb out of their 2-0 deficit against the San Antonio 
Spurs. It is the equivalent of third-and-long with the clock 
running and no timeouts. 
</P>
<P>
	For a change, there is talk of taking the ball out of Ward's  
hands. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why would we change?'' Ward said, referring to speculation  
that Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy will send Ward to the bench in 
favor of a bigger backcourt of Latrell Sprewell and Allan Houston 
in Game 3 Monday night. ``It's not about a lineup change. That's 
only for you guys to talk about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a quarterback, Ward always seemed able to make something out  
of nothing. As point guard of the Knicks, he has yet to make 
anything look easy against the Spurs. 
</P>
<P>
	Ward, never as potent on the court as he was on the gridiron,  
has 12 points in two games in the finals. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks, struggling to find enough offense with Patrick Ewing  
out and Larry Johnson hobbled with a knee injury, might need to try 
something different in the backcourt. Ward's backup, Chris Childs, 
is 3-for-16 in the series. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Knicks beat the New Jersey Nets late in the season,  
Nets point guard Stephon Marbury left no doubt about his opinion of 
Ward and Childs. 
</P>
<P>
	``They'll never win a championship with those two guys -- never,  
ever, ever,'' Marbury said. ``It's just not going to happen. They 
might not even make the playoffs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, Ward responded simply by saying, ``I'm not here to  
please any man. I'm not here to talk about anyone else, so you're 
not going to get me caught up in that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spurs point guard Avery Johnson deflected any credit for the  
Knicks' point guard woes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mark Jackson, in the last series, they needed him to score for  
Indiana to even have a chance,'' Johnson said. ``So with Charlie 
and Chris, their main job is to play defense and to get the ball to 
other guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Ward has any fight left in him, he showed a glimpse of it  
when asked about the lack of production from the Knicks' point 
guards. 
</P>
<P>
	``What do you mean lack of?'' Ward said disdainfully. ``We've  
done a good job of getting the ball to guys, we just haven't made 
the shots that we've needed to. It's not just the point guards, 
it's everyone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For someone who says he hates the spotlight, Ward has held two  
of the most visible, pressurized positions in sports: quarterback 
of Bobby Bowden's Seminoles and point guard of the Knicks. The 
folks in Thomasville, Ga., would add quarterback and point guard at 
Central High School to the list, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do I love being in the spotlight? No,'' Ward said. ``I enjoy  
doing my job. Being in the spotlight is not something that I enjoy 
doing, because if I did, I would do crazy things to gain attention 
when I'm not getting attention. And that's the last thing that I'm 
trying to do. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't need attention or glamour to be successful.''  
</P>
<P>
	Ward has always grasped the meaning of a big game. There is one  
of those scheduled for Monday night at Madison Square Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	It remains to be seen whether Ward will start, or how much he  
will play. 
</P>
<P>
	If he does, it will be as big as any bowl game for him.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
