<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 11:50:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Korea Conglomerates Face Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- For the chairman of the chemical giant  
Hanwha, the past year and a half has been ``like going through a 
major surgery without anesthesia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hanwha's sales tumbled by half as it sold off one asset after  
another to raise desperately needed cash during the recession 
brought on by Asia's economic crisis. Its subsidiaries were pared 
down to 20 from 32. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a terrible sense of deprivation,'' says Lee Yong-ho,  
Hanwha's chief finance officer and the engineer of its 
restructuring. 
</P>
<P>
	``But we know better now. We don't mind being small now. We want  
to be a company of substance. It no longer matters how many 
affiliates we have now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For a South Korean conglomerate, that is a momentous change in  
thinking. 
</P>
<P>
	Hanwha is one of South Korea's family-run conglomerates, called  
``chaebol,'' which are known for their aversion to change and for 
their deep pride in a sprawling portfolio. 
</P>
<P>
	For them, business was always about size, their clout measured  
by the number of subsidiaries. Profit was secondary, market share 
everything. Selling assets was considered a big loss of face. 
</P>
<P>
	Not everyone has changed. Two years into Asia's economic slump,  
the five biggest chaebol -- Hyundai, Samsung, Daewoo, LG and SK -- 
continue to amass assets in a development that international and 
local officials say could threaten South Korea's long-term 
recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	But dozens of smaller chaebol are trimming down and focusing on  
profitability -- Hanwha a bright example among them. 
</P>
<P>
	Hanwha started as a small company making gunpowder for the South  
Korean military in the 1960s. Over the decades it diversified into 
petrochemicals, machinery, auto parts, oil refining, distribution 
and hotels. 
</P>
<P>
	Debt-financed expansion was the norm among chaebol from the  
1970s to early 1990s, when they fueled South Korea's stunning 
economic growth. Loaded with cash, banks doled out more loans when 
old ones came due. 
</P>
<P>
	``In those days, we never had a problem with the availability of  
bank credits,'' Lee says. ``When that began to change in 1997, we 
were in big trouble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Asia's financial storms swept into South Korea in late 1997  
and banks tightened credit, Hanwha, then the country's eighth 
largest chaebol, with $10 billion in annual sales, was the first 
pushed to the brink of bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
	It avoided collapse at the last minute when the government  
ordered creditor banks to funnel $541 million in emergency loans to 
Hanwha in a desperate attempt to contain the spread of panic in the 
corporate sector. 
</P>
<P>
	It was then that Hanwha initiated its dramatic switch.  
</P>
<P>
	In his office, Chairman Kim Seung-youn put up an ancient Korean  
battlefield motto meant to inspire daring: ``Vow to live, and you 
will die! Vow to die, and you will live!'' 
</P>
<P>
	With that, Hanwha began jettisoning prized assets -- with  
singular speed. 
</P>
<P>
	So far it has:  
</P>
<P>
	--Sold all or part of 12 affiliates, including 70 percent of its  
profitable ball bearing division to Germany's FAG Kugelfischer 
Georg Schaefer AG. 
</P>
<P>
	--Agreed to sell Hanwha Energy, its biggest subsidiary and  
generator of one-third of its total revenues, to rival Hyundai 
Refinery Co. 
</P>
<P>
	--Unloaded 32 pieces of prime real estate.  
</P>
<P>
	--Shed one-fourth of its 20,000 workers. For those who remain,  
wages were frozen and bimonthly bonuses halved. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a tough time for both the company and workers. When the  
company started restructuring, old workers felt the pressure to 
retire early,'' said Kim Soo-bong, 45, who left Hanwha in early 
1998 after 18 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Through its crash diet, Hanwha unloaded $3 billion in debt and  
raised more than $840 million in cash to lower its debt-to-equity 
ratio to 250 percent from 1,200 percent at the end of 1997 -- a task 
locally praised as the best example of the kind of restructuring 
ordered by President Kim Dae-jung. 
</P>
<P>
	Hanwha lost $140 million last year on sales of $5.1 billion.  
Kim, the chairman, projects a net profit of $250 million this year 
on revenue of $6.25 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors have taken heart. Share prices of Hanwha's two main  
subsidiaries, Hanwha Corp. and Hanwha Chemical Corp., have climbed 
to around $7.50 from last year's low of $1.70. 
</P>
<P>
	Hanwha says it will continue to chop off affiliates and fold  
them into a half dozen nimble, competitive businesses in chemicals, 
retail distribution, leisure facilities and financing. 
</P>
<P>
	``One year ago, when I came to the office in the morning, I  
could almost smell defeat. Now a sense of confidence is spreading 
that we can pull it off,'' says Lee Myong-sop, a middle manager. 
</P>
<P>
	``The past year was a hard time, but a good lesson.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
