<DOCNO> APW19990620.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 09:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yosemite Climb Had Unexpected Risk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YOSEMITE NATIONAL PARK, Calif. (AP) -- When the dust settled,  
Peter Terbush was still clutching the rope. But he didn't survive 
the rock slide that crashed down on his head, and his buddies can't 
believe they did. 
</P>
<P>
	The three experienced climbers were using proper equipment to  
scale Yosemite National Park's Glacier Point Apron, a granite slab 
attractive to newcomers unfamiliar with the territory. 
</P>
<P>
	``That area has great, easy climbing. Beginners love to go there  
because the climb is not real steep,'' said Dave Bengston, director 
of Yosemite Mountaineering School. 
</P>
<P>
	But if the three Colorado climbers had asked, Bengston would  
have warned them away from the slab of rock behind Curry Village. 
</P>
<P>
	It's risky in the spring, when snowmelt can seep into cracks in  
the cliff and freeze during the night, expanding and loosening the 
rock. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I do go there, it's big-time helmet zone,'' said Bengston.  
``That place makes me nervous. I hear rocks coming down all the 
time. All winter long, it was constant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the danger, rock climbing is increasingly popular and  
Yosemite stands as the ``center of the universe,'' attracting 
climbers from all over the globe to challenge granite monoliths 
that stand thousands of feet high. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people breathe, I climb,'' said Dylan Morgan, a  
22-year-old search and rescue team candidate at Yosemite. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of the challenge of scaling rocks and cliffs is knowing how  
to eliminate or minimize the risks, he says. ``(A) thousand things 
can go wrong when you're up there, but millions of things could go 
right,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Terbush's companions, Joe Kewin and Kerry Pyle, said they had  
talked to other climbers about the area and didn't think anything 
would happen. Besides, their climb on June 13 was only supposed to 
take about half an hour. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a famous climb. It had some of the best cracks in the  
valley,'' said Kewin, 21. 
</P>
<P>
	There were even fresh chalk marks from the hands of climbers who  
must have been there shortly before, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Terbush stood at the base of the granite face, anchoring the  
belay rope for 20-year-old Pyle as he began scaling the cliff that 
rises towards Glacier Point, a spot with a panoramic view 3,000 
feet above Yosemite Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	Kewin stood behind Terbush, 22.  
</P>
<P>
	They were only planning a short climb, about 300 feet up and  
then back down. 
</P>
<P>
	Pyle had climbed up about 70 feet -- the equivalent of a  
seven-story building -- when they heard what sounded like a clap of 
thunder. 
</P>
<P>
	They were showered at first with small rocks, but then came  
boulders the size of Volkswagens. 
</P>
<P>
	Terbush, a third-generation climber who began rock climbing at  
age 11 with his father, stood his ground. When the billows of dust 
cleared, his hands were still clutching the rope that prevented 
Pyle from falling. 
</P>
<P>
	But he was dead of a massive head wound. Pyle suffered scrapes  
and bruises. Kewin had only a few cuts, and had to pry Terbush's 
fingers from the rope in order to help Pyle down from the cliff. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of us should have died,'' said Pyle. ``Joe and I are lucky  
to be alive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pyle and Kewin didn't know what they could have done  
differently. 
</P>
<P>
	And they wanted to try climbing again before leaving the park --  
if only to prove to themselves that they could still do it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to deal with my emotions. I want to see how I feel.  
Climbing is a huge thing in my life,'' Pyle said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
