<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Freedom Riders Remember Slain Youth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA, Miss. (AP) -- Mississippi has failed to bring  
justice to the families of three slain civil rights workers, a 
group of youth leaders and veterans of the 1964 freedom ride said 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	More than a hundred gathered to urge the state to reopen the  
case 35 years after the killings of James Chaney, Andrew Goodman 
and Mickey Schwerner. 
</P>
<P>
	The congregation, which included dozens of young people who are  
traveling by bus to re-create the historic ``Freedom Rides'' 
through the South, went to the spot where the three were killed in 
Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am feeling sadness for the fact that my brother is dead,''  
Ben Chaney, brother of James Chaney, said during the ceremony 
marking the 35th anniversary of the deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	``His companions are dead and the state of Mississippi has yet  
to fulfill it's judicial responsibility by prosecuting those who 
conspired and committed the murders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chaney, Schwerner and Goodman were traveling down a Neshoba  
County road on the night of June 21, 1964 when they were ambushed 
by the Ku Klux Klan and shot to death. Their bodies were not found 
until 44 days later when the FBI recovered them from an earthen 
dam. 
</P>
<P>
	The three were part of the group Congress on Racial Equality,  
which organized voter registration drives across the South. 
</P>
<P>
	No one has been convicted of their murders. Seven Klansmen,  
including a sheriff's deputy, were convicted of federal conspiracy 
charges. The investigation has been renewed, but Neshoba County 
District Attorney Ken Turner refuses to comment on the case. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
