<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-20 20:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Wants Tougher Gun Show Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton appealed Sunday from Europe  
for the House to reverse course and impose tougher controls on gun 
show sales. Top congressional Democrats looked to use the issue to 
the party's advantage in next year's elections. 
</P>
<P>
	A leading House Republican accused the Democrats of playing  
politics with the issue. Rep. Tom DeLay, the majority whip, blamed 
Democrats for defeating the gun legislation even though Republicans 
agreed to some controls. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate's top Democrat, Tom Daschle of South Dakota, said  
there a ``glimmer of hope'' congressional negotiators working on a 
major juvenile crime bill would include gun control measures 
approved by the Senate but rejected by the House. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are going to fight as hard as we possibly can,'' Daschle  
said on CBS' ``Face the Nation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, in a CNN interview in Cologne, Germany, where he was  
attending a summit of world leaders, pointed to the success of the 
Brady law, which requires background checks on handgun buyers. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past five years, the law has kept guns out of the hands  
of an estimated 400,000 unqualified buyers. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton repeated an appeal, made in his weekly radio address  
taped Saturday, that lawmakers approve background checks on gun 
sales at flea markets and gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	The president said no one seriously has questioned ``there would  
be fewer improper sales and we would make America safer'' if 
lawmakers approved those checks. 
</P>
<P>
	Daschle and the House's Democratic leader, Rep. Dick Gephardt of  
Missouri, believe Democrats can gain politically from gun control. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this is going to be a very powerful issue'' in the  
coming election,'' Daschle said, given the public's demand for 
tighter controls following the April school shooting in Littleton, 
Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	Gephardt, appearing on ABC's ``This Week,'' said a small number  
of voters would oppose any gun control advocates. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem is the 80 percent who are for gun safety, just  
aren't for it very much, they are not intense,'' Gephardt said, 
adding that it essential to appeal to his large part of the 
electorate. 
</P>
<P>
	``It can be run on and it can be won on in any district in this  
country,'' Gephardt said. 
</P>
<P>
	DeLay, R-Texas, said it was the Democrats who played politics on  
the issue. He said Republicans agreed to require that safety locks 
be sold with guns and to ban some ammunition clips, but Democrats 
still brought the gun legislation to defeat. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a great week for us,'' he said on ABC, citing  
approval of legislation that addresses the spiritual education of 
children while imposing tougher penalties for youth crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats led the effort to defeat the gun control portion of  
the juvenile crime bill. The defeat followed House passage of a 
provision, written by Democrat Rep. John Dingell of Michigan and 
backed by Republicans, that Democrats said drastically weakened the 
background checks. 
</P>
<P>
	Dingell's amendment reduced the amount of time allowed for the  
check from three days to 24 hours in all cases. In addition, it 
would have defined gun shows in a way to exclude some events that 
are now covered. 
</P>
<P>
	Dingell, interviewed on ``Fox News Sunday,'' said he thought 24  
hours was ``quite sufficient'' to check backgrounds and ``see to it 
that innocent and law-abiding citizens are not harassed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dingell, the senior Democrat in the House, said Democratic  
support for gun control legislation ``probably did cost us the 
Congress'' in the 1994 election. He said the party, in seeking to 
stop youth violence, should concentrate on other issues such as 
health care programs for troubled youngsters. 
</P>
<P>
	DeLay also said that 24 hours was enough to check would-be gun  
buyers, particularly if the FBI agreed to stay open on weekends, 
when many of the gun shows take place. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
